<HEADLINE> U.N. Humanitarian Workers Leave Jordan for Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 22 (Xinhua) - Over 100 U.N. humanitarian
workers Tuesday left Amman for Baghdad as required by the U.N.
following the end of U.S.-led air attacks on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. spokesman said in a brief statement in Amman that the
U.N. workers were from nine U.N. organizations, including the
World Food Program, U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization, the
World Health Organization, the United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), the United Nations
International Children's Emergency Fund (UNICEF) and other
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. workers, who had been based in Baghdad, were evacuated
to Amman last week after the U.S. and British forces launched the
air attacks on Baghdad for Iraq's alleged non-cooperation with
U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian-Iraqi border remained the only land exit from
Iraq due to the non-fly zones imposed by the U.S.-led
multi-national forces after the 1991 Gulf war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
