<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Bankruptcies Declining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The number of bankruptcies in
Germany is continuing to drop, after several years of rising
insolvencies, according to a report republished from the Federal
Statistics Office Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In this October, company bankruptcies in Germany accounted for
2164, down 9.8 per cent from the same month last year, the German
Statistics Office reported.
</P>
<P>
The Office reported, for the first ten months of 1998, the
number of company bankruptcies came to 22228, 1.3 per cent over
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
But since last summer the figures have been dropping on a
year-to-year basis, with the August-October three-month totals
down by 6.3 per cent from the same months of 1997, the statistics
report said.
</P>
<P>
In an east-west breakdown, bankruptcies in western Germany in
October came to 1908, down 11.5 per cent, while the ten-month
total was 20209, up a scant 0.1 per cent over 1997 figures.
</P>
<P>
In eastern Germany, October bankruptcies came to 705, down by
8.3 per cent, while the ten-month total was 8019, up 4.4 per cent.
</P>
</TEXT>
