<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho People Urged to Rebuild Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Maseru, the
capital of Lesotho, have been urged to work together to rebuild
their city, Southern African Broadcasting Association (SABA)
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mohau Kobile, mayor of Maseru, was quoted as saying that all
people in the country should have a spirit of development, and
work to lead Lesotho into a brighter future.
</P>
<P>
The mayor said that the Maseru City Council had made
preparations to work hard in the new year.
</P>
<P>
Most of businesses and residential houses in Maseru were
burned down during political disturbances on September 22.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 people were killed in the political unrest which
started on August 4.
</P>
<P>
Trouble in the mountainous kingdom followed the opposition's
rejection of the May general elections, in which the ruling
Lesotho Congress of Democracy (LCD) was accused of rigging in its
own favor.
</P>
<P>
The conflict worsened after soldiers rebelled and arrested
their officers, accusing the government of failing to check the
violent protests which followed.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili had to call for help
from the Southern African Development Community (SADC), and was
bailed out by South African and Botswanan troops.
</P>
<P>
The rebelling Lesotho Defense Force soldiers later surrendered
to the intervention forces after weeks of burning, fighting and
looting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
