<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lithuania Abolishes Death Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Despite widespread public
doubt, Lithuania has abolished death penalty, Interfax reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under amendments to the criminal code passed Monday evening by
the Lithuanian parliament the capital punishment will be replaced
by life imprisonment for very serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
Public reaction to the abolition is mixed in the face of
growing crimes in the Baltic country. Polls found that about 70-80
percent of the public find it premature, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
The abolition was initiated by President Valdas Adamkus after
the Constitutional Court ruled that death sentences contradicted
the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The parliament also passed a law commuting the sentence of the
country's nine inmates to life imprisonment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
