<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Discovers Illegal Cotton Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The state-owned
Tanzania Cotton Lint and Seed Board (TCLSB) has discovered nine
companies and a cooperative society illegally exporting cotton to
neighboring Kenya.
</P>
<P>
TCLSB General Manager Ali Ngongolo revealed here Tuesday that
the illegal exports have denied the board 7,984,656 Shillings
(about 11,800 U.S. Dollars) of revenue.
</P>
<P>
Ngongolo claimed that Dan P. Makaranga, Mara Oil Mill, Copcot
Cotton, S and G Ginning Company, Virian (T) Limited, Bibiti Oil
Ltd, and Nyanza Cooperative Union (NCU) have involved themselves
in illicit deals this year.
</P>
<P>
Other companies that have violated export regulations in the
year include Birchand Ltd, Rift Valley and Cream Cotton, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ngongolo noted that a total of 6,161 bales of cotton have been
sent to Kenya through Siari and other border stations without the
permission of his board and it is not known how such a big
consignment could cross the border.
</P>
<P>
The board has directed these companies and the NCU to get
necessary permits and pay levy, otherwise legal action will be
taken against them.
</P>
<P>
According to the general manager, exporters of cotton are
obliged to get export permits as well as certificates of quality
from the board.
</P>
<P>
He also said that investigations concerning other border
stations will continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Stops Considering START Ratification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Russia's top legislator said
Tuesday that the State Duma has closed debates on ratifying the
START II treaty in the aftermath of the military strikes on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The militaristic action against Iraq, conducted in the
immediate proximity to the southern borders of the Commonwealth of
Independent States, should seriously prompt the strengthening of
the defense capability of not only Russia but the CIS as a
whole," said Gennady Seleznyov, speaker of the State Duma, or
lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
"We must start developing our common defense doctrine so that
in the future no one could have illusions about the possibility of
knocking us off one by one," Seleznyov's spokesman Mikhail Belyat
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the United Nations to immediately start an
inquiry into the activity of Richard Butler as head of the U.N.
Special Commission on Iraq (UNSCOM), and dismiss him from office.
</P>
<P>
"Butler's mission was quite reminiscent of a spying mission,
however, the U.N. commission cannot and must not fulfill an
assignment from the CIA or the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff,"
Seleznyov said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the U.N. Security Council to speak up on the
issue. "One cannot keep silent or make it look as if nothing
extraordinary has taken place without harming his own prestige."
</P>
<P>
Russia and the United States signed START II in 1993, and the
U.S. Senate ratified it in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Many deputies of the State Duma believe that the pact could
weaken Russia's security and would be too expensive to implement.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaty, both countries will cut their nuclear
arsenals in half to about 3,000 to 3,500 warheads each.
</P>
<P>
Russian military officials say many of the country's nuclear
weapons are nearing the end of their service life and will have to
be dismantled in any case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
