<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Students Protest Against Airstrikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 22 (Xinhua) -- More than one thousand
students at Lebanon's public and private universities Tuesday
staged a protest against the U.S.-led airstrikes on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Amid tight security measures around the U.S. embassy in east
Beirut, students gathered around the fortress-like compound,
chanting anti-U.S. slogans and setting the U.S. flags on fire.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration, the first ever in the country in five years,
came one day after the newly formed cabinet lifted the ban on
street protests.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon imposed a ban on demonstrations after nine people were
killed in clashes between troops and demonstrators who protested
the 1993 Oslo Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Students denounced the airstrikes launched by U.S. and British
forces last week and demanded the shutting down of the
U.S. embassy in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
During the protest, Lebanese security forces kept some
distance between the angry students and the embassy in order to
avert protests similar to those in Syria last week, during which
demonstrators broke into the U.S. embassy and removed the
U.S. flag from the top of the building.
</P>
<P>
Similar demonstrations were also held in front of the British
embassy in east Beirut, whose service offices were closed during
the day for security reasons, an embassy official said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British forces launched airstrikes against Iraq
under the pretext of Iraqi incomplete cooperation with
U.N. weapons inspection team, which is charged with disarming
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
At least 62 Iraqi soldiers were killed and another 180 wounded
during the four-day air raids. 
</P>
</TEXT>
