<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO: More Time Needed to Obtain Evidence on War-Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) said here Tuesday that it would be unreasonable to expect
accurate data by 1999 at the earliest to support Iraqi allegations
that shells with depleted uranium increased incidents of cancer
and leukaemia in the country.
</P>
<P>
"During the Gulf War (1990-1991) the military is reported to
have used depleted uranium for shell casings as a hardening agent.
This has resulted in radiation exposure in the battle zones in the
south of the country," said WHO.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, local health authorities report increase in the
occurrence of many health conditions, including growth
retardation, congenital malformations, abortion, infertility,
myxoedema, cataract, uraemia and cancer," it said. "Of immediate
concern is the reported increase in frequency of leukaemia in
reports to the central registry from the southern governorates."
</P>
<P>
Upon the request of the Ministry of Health of Iraq, a WHO
mission visited the country from August 9 to 13, 1998 to evaluate
the cancer registration system and the implication of the use of
depleted uranium and to make recommendations for future
developments.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations made by the team include measures to
upgrade the central population-based registry in Baghdad,
establishing a second registry in Basra, in addition to the one
functioning in Mosul, and strengthening active data collection.
</P>
<P>
"WHO is seeking the resources needed to strengthen research and
treatment of emerging diseases such as leukaemia and cancers,"
said WHO. "The objective is to establish with the Iraqi Health
Ministry a capacity to deal with the surveillance, prevention and
treatment of cancer and other emerging diseases." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
