<HEADLINE> Estonian Transport Workers to Boycott Finnish Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Estonian transport workers
plan to declare a boycott on Finnish cargo ships, an Estonian
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Juri Lember, chairman of the Confederation of Estonian
Transport Workers' Union, told the Postimees that the action would
be taken in response to the boycott of Estonian ships declared by
the Finnish transport workers' unions, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
"There is almost no doubt this action will go ahead," Lember
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Finnish ships will be treated the same way as
Estonian ships are treated in Finland - they will not be loaded or
unloaded.
</P>
<P>
"In accordance with Estonian laws, this measure can be applied
for three days," Lember said.
</P>
<P>
The row started at the beginning of December, when the Finnish
union of transport workers refused to unload Estonian ships,
saying that the Estonian sailors' wages were too low.
</P>
<P>
On December 15, the Finnish transport workers were joined by
dockers of the Danish port of Orhus.
</P>
<P>
In the opinion of the Estonian sea shipping line, the Finnish
and Danish boycott is aimed at forcing Estonia out of the
Helsinki-Muugas (Estonia)-Orhus line operated by the Finnish
company Finncarriers.
</P>
<P>
The Estonian shipping line has sent a letter to the Helsinki
district court urging it to suspend the boycott of Estonian ships
pending the investigation into its legality, Interfax said.
</P>
</TEXT>
