<HEADLINE> Greece, Romania Agree to Strengthen Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Romania Tuesday
agreed to strengthen military cooperation between the two
countries following the talks between Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos and his visiting Romanian counterpart, Victor
Babiuc.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed to expand their cooperation in the sector of
armaments, the defense industry, military training and periodic
meetings of officials of the respective ministries for monitoring
progress, according to the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA).
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two ministers also expressed concern
about the situation in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, saying
that if peace talks between parties concerned did not begin by the
end of winter, the tension in the region would be intensified in
March.
</P>
<P>
As for the recent air strikes launched jointly by the U.S. and
Britain against Iraq, Babiuc said that the use of force should
always be "a last resort" for resolving problems.
</P>
<P>
Solutions should result from compromise through peaceful means,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian minister invited Greece and the U.S. to
participate in cooperation among the countries of the Black Sea
region as well as among the armed forces of the region. 
</P>
