<HEADLINE> Arab League Urges Peaceful Solution to Iraqi Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdel-Meguid Tuesday called for world efforts to
reach a peaceful solution to the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid made the call in his messages to U.N. chief Kofi
Annan and Chinese, French and Russian foreign ministers, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He urged the world community to stress the stance on rejecting
the use of force in dealing with international relations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched four days of air strikes on Iraq
last week to retaliate what U.S. President Bill Clinton said
Baghdad's defiance of the U.N. arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
China, Russia and the AL have denounced the air raids.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid underlined the need for the U.N. Security Council
to shoulder its responsibilities through a new mechanism for
monitoring Iraq's weapons program.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said a new mechanism should be assigned to
provide confidence, solve pending issues between Iraq and the
U.N., ensure the implementation of relevant U.N. resolutions and
expedite the lifting of the crippling economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The existing mechanism for weapons inspections in Iraq is the
U.N. Special Commission which Iraq has accused of serving the
interests of the United States and Britain only.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid also stressed that Iraq's sovereignty, unity and
territorial integrity must be respected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
