<HEADLINE> Kyrgyz Probe Continues on Corruption in Finance Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyz Interior Minister
Omurbek Kutuyev said Tuesday that the probe into alleged
corruption and embezzlement in the Finance Ministry is continuing.
</P>
<P>
Kutuyev told lawmakers that charges of embezzlement, fraud and
corruption had been brought against detained ministry officials.
About 35 such facts have been checked, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyz Prosecutor-General Asanbek Sharshenaliyev said that if
the corruption charges are not confirmed, the cases will be
closed.
</P>
<P>
He said a task force combating corruption plans to detain and
bring charges against several more state officials. He did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Talaibek Koichumanov has sharply condemned the
arrest of Finance Ministry officials, saying the announcement of
an indictment prior to a court decision is a gross violation of
human rights.
</P>
<P>
He also accused law-enforcement officers of blackmailing and
slandering the defendants.
</P>
<P>
"A good initiative to combat corruption, advanced by the
president, has been discredited," Koichumanov said.
</P>
<P>
"The Finance Ministry is not guilty of anything," the minister
claimed.
</P>
<P>
The former Soviet republic has stepped up its fight against
corruption in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Hot lines are being installed in the country to handle
complaints about corrupt officials, Shirshenaliyev, the
prosecutor-general announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Shirshenaliyev heads the Coordinating Council Against
Corruption and Economic Crime, a task force created by President
Askar Akayev on December 19.
</P>
<P>
The council, which includes representatives of security and law
enforcement structures, tax agencies, customs structures and the
prosecutor's office, will take steps to tighten the struggle
against corruption, Shirshenaliyev said.
</P>
<P>
Government comptrollers and the Presidential Administration
will be assisting the council, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new structure will control the investigation of all
corruption charges in the country, the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
He said 383 officials had been dismissed over the past five
years on charges of corruption. The majority of crimes involving
abuse of office were committed by low-level rather than by senior
officials, Shirshenaliyev said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
