<HEADLINE> Kuwait's Parliament Passes Bill on Expatriates' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's parliament
Tuesday approved a bill on health insurance for expatriates,
ending the era of free medical services for foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which is aimed at imposing charges on state-run
services, was passed by a vote of 35-1, with two abstentions in
the first reading.
</P>
<P>
The bill said a expatriate cannot obtain a residence permit
unless having a health insurance certificate or a health insurance
contract.
</P>
<P>
The parliament allows the Health Ministry to word its
regulations within a year.
</P>
<P>
The welfare state Kuwait, with expatriates accounting for
nearly 81 percent of its 2.1 million people, provided free medical
services to both its citizens and foreign residents.
</P>
<P>
But the dramatical fall of state revenues arising from the
sagging oil prices in recent years have forced the government to
cut spending to contain the inflating state budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's Health Minister Adel Al-Subeih said last September
that the current budget will not meet the Health Ministry's
requirements.
</P>
<P>
Adel pointed out the proposed health insurance system is not a
revenue-booster for the ministry, just an alleviation to its
burden.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, each expatriate will be obliged to pay 50-70
Kuwaiti dinars (165-230 U.S. dollars) in insurance premium per
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
