<HEADLINE> U.S. Opposed to Lift Sanctions against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States opposes
any effort to lift economic sanctions against Iraq and
would use its veto power in the U.N. Security Council to keep
them in place, the White House said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly oppose any effort to dismantle the sanctions
regime and if it meant using our veto, we would," White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He also said U.N. weapons inspectors should be allowed to
continue their work in Iraq if they could be allowed to operate
effectively.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that an effective UNSCOM is the best way to
contain Saddam Hussein's ability to reconstitute and deliver his
weapons of mass destruction," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council is assessing its Iraq policies after
four days of air strikes by the United States and Britain. Iraq
has rejected any return of weapons inspectors and is calling for
an end to sweeping sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. weapons inspectors left Baghdad last Wednesday just
hours before the air strikes began.
</P>
<P>
France and Germany have suggested trying to find a new
approach to controlling Iraqi weapons of mass destruction, which
could lead to an easing of economic sanctions.  
</P>
