<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Jiang Calls for Action to Prevent Unstability (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese president Jiang Zemin
warned today that if certain social and economic problems were not
tackled without delay, the overall stability of the country could
be threatened.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also general secretary of the Chinese Communist Party
Central Committee, said that the economic returns of a number of
state-owned enterprises are not good, the army of redundant
workers is growing and they have difficulties in their life, and
that farmers in certain rural areas have seen their income
dwindling and their financial burdens are increasing. And in some
parts of the country people are complaining about the rising crime
rate.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the concluding session of a national conference
focused on China's political and legal frameworks, the Chinese
leader said 1999 will be of great significance for China as the
country will celebrate its 50th birthday and resume its right of
exercising sovereignty over Macao.
</P>
<P>
Jiang urged those in judicial and public security departments
to be vigilant and remain tough on crime, stressing that social
stability is the paramount task for China next year.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that today's world is by no means peaceful, with
hegemony rife and worldwide power politics still looming large on
the horizon. The trend towards economic globalization is a grave
challenge to China in protecting itself in terms of economic
security.
</P>
<P>
He called for a program of political and ideological education
among the general public to "enhance their awareness and
capability to fight against the infiltration by both domestic and
foreign hostile forces."
</P>
<P>
Jiang said: "Any factors that could jeopardize our stability
must be annihilated in the early stages. This policy has been
proved by our past experience and is very important and
effective," said Jiang.
</P>
</TEXT>
