<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nanjing Residents Condemn Verdict of Japanese Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Many Nanjing residents today
condemned the verdict of a Japanese court which ruled that
soldiers named in a war-time diary about the Nanjing Massacre
cannot be brought to trial.
</P>
<P>
From all walks of life, they gathered in a museum built to
commemorate the 300,000 people killed by Japanese soldiers in the
infamous December 1937 Nanjing Massacre.
</P>
<P>
The names of some of those who perpetrated the evil deeds
had been listed in the diary of Shiro Azuma, a former Japanese
soldier who witnessed the incident and recorded it.
</P>
<P>
Shiro Azuma published his diary in April 1996 and was promptly
sued by a man listed in it and named as a war criminal. The Tokyo
Higher Court ruled in the man's favor, that his name should not be
publicised or any action taken.
</P>
<P>
Azuma, who feels justice should be done, appealed to a higher
court but that appeal was rejected this month.
</P>
<P>
According to Gao Xingzu, a professor with the Department of
History at Nanjing University and chairman of the Nanjing Massacre
Historical Society said that the verdict only demonstrates that
the Japanese right-wing elements have never been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
"The massacre has been consistently and universally condemned
by the nations worldwide, including military tribunals," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jingcheng, vice-chairman of the Nanjing Law Society,
revealed that Shiro Azuma and his lawyer has come to Nanjing twice
to collect evidence of the massacre, to no avail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
