<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DNA Samples Urged for Air Crews in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Canadian flight crews and
frequent flyers should have their fingerprints and DNA samples
stored with their employers or the government,  newspapers here
said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After spending 105 days identifying the fragmented remains of
the 229 passengers and crew of Swissair Flight 111, a senior
officer from the Royal Canadian Mounted Police RCMP) said the
RCMP would recommend to the federal Transportation Safety Board
TSB) that all Canadian air crews should have their personal
information stored with their airlines or with the board itself,
to be used only in case of a crash.
</P>
<P>
"(An air disaster) is a remote possibility and it continues to
be a remote possibility, basically proven by the statistics. It
(providing samples) is strictly an individual's choice. We are
only recommending this for the flight crews," said Steve Duncan,
the RCMP's top crash investigator, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But Canadian airlines are approaching the RCMP recommendations
cautiously, recognizing that mandatory fingerprinting or DNA
testing is fraught with human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for Air Canada said that her company had not
considered storing fingerprints or doing DNA testing for its
employees but would review the legal and labor issues involved if
the TSB recommended it.
</P>
<P>
She said at one time the airline fingerprinted its cabin crews
but stopped because it was unnecessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
