<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt is concerned that the recent U.S.-British
airstrikes against Iraq may set obstacles to the implementation of
the "oil-for-food" deal and delay the payment of compensations to
Egyptians whose interests sustained damage in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Egypt had approximately 293,000 dollars in decided
compensations to cover the category A beneficiaries and the
category C holders who had suffered property damages of up to
100,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has so far received about 490 million dollars in
compensations, benefiting about 191,000 Egyptians who had left
Kuwait or Iraq during the period from August 1990 to March 1991.
</P>
<P>
JEDDA -- Saudi Arabia's ARAMCO company announced Wednesday
that it has approved three tenders for the construction of a new
oil refinery in Al Hawiya area, east of Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
The first project covers such utilities as gas treatment, gas
concentration and pressure. The second project involves the inputs
and outputs and other auxiliary utilities of the refinery.
</P>
<P>
The third project entails utilities that extract sulphur as well
as loading utilities. ARAMCO sources said that "it was virtually
decided to complete the gas refinery in Al Hawiya" by April 2002.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) Airlines has received
its ninth and last long-range Boeing 777/200 jet, considered as
the most advanced passenger planes in the world.
</P>
<P>
The UAE Airlines has ordered two more planes of Boeing 777/300
type, Egyptian daily "Alam Al Yom" reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
They will join the Airlines fleet by the end of 1999. And the
UAE Airlines will open two new routes, to Islamabad and Lahore in
Pakistan, as from the beginning of next year. This will add its
destinations to 47 in 37 countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran is to set up a gasoline unit at the Turkmen
Bashi refinery according to an agreement reached between Tehran
and Ashkhabad.
</P>
<P>
Karim Tafreshi, head of the Iranian Oil ministry Office in
Turkmenistan, said that the accord was finalized early this week
and the project would cost some 50 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
