<HEADLINE> France Suggests Continuous Arms Control over Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In an interview with the daily Liberation, French Foreign Minis
ter Hubert Vedrine said that "a new system, not of investigation
on the past, but of precautions for the future," could be set up
to replace the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of
destruction of arms of mass destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"A continuous control would consist first of all of surveying
any re-launch by Iraq of the production of prohibited weapons. It
would also seek to prevent the continuous deterioration of the
humanitarian situation in Iraq," Vedrine said.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the new control system also serve as the
basis for a lifting of U.N. sanctions against Iraq imposed since
the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
He said that France shares the "same objective" with the
United States on Iraq, which aims at preventing the country from
becoming dangerous again.
</P>
<P>
"Our common objective is the establishment of a real
continuous control system over armament and the oil income (of
Iraq), which would gather the conditions of security that allow
the lifting of oil embargo." he said.
</P>
<P>
However, it was reported that the United States has rejected
the French proposal for a new control system and said that the
UNSCOM should remain in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
