<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Insists on Peaceful Solution to Angola Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUANDA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- United Nations special
representative to Angola, Issa Diallo, said Wednesday that the
Angolan crisis could be settled only through peaceful
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Diallo made the remarks here in response to a statement
issued Tuesday by the Angolan government, which blamed the U.N.
for biasing and conniving at UNITA's actions.
</P>
<P>
Only through negotiations, including persuading those who
have chosen the language of war to give up the military option,
can the crisis facing Angola be resolved, the U.N. envoy
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The statement attributed the fierce fighting which broke out
again in central Angola between the government army and the
troops of the opposition National Union for Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) to the "bias and connivance" of the U.N. observer
mission at UNITA's actions.
</P>
<P>
It urged the U.N. to follow the stance of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) by declaring UNITA President
Jonas Savimbi to be a "war criminal" and considering the UNITA
breakaway group Renovation Commission as the sole lawful
dialogist so as to fulfill all the tasks prescribed in the 1994
Lusaka peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy said it is "understandable" that the Angolan
government showed dismay becaused the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol
was not comprehensively implemented.
</P>
<P>
"We can understand the stance mentioned by the Angolan
government#," he said. "But we hope that they can also understand
ours. That is, everything should be good for peace and
reconciliation among all the Angolan people."
</P>
<P>
A military source disclosed that the government troops dealt
a severe blow at the UNITA forces in the battlefield near Kuito,
recapturing the strategic town of Cunhinga, 30 km northwest of
Kuito, along with cannons and armored vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Kuito has been surrounded by the UNITA troops for more than
half a month and the seisure of Cunhinga has greatly released the
pressure upon the government troops defending the capital of Bie
province.
</P>
<P>
However, the source warned people against being over
optimistic since the areas around Kuito are still in the hands of
the UNITA forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
