<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koirala Named PM of New Govt in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Congress (NC)
President Girija Prasad Koirala, who resigned Monday as Nepal's
prime minister, was appointed Wednesday by King Birendra as
expected to head a new coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Koirala has won enough support of 135 lawmakers from his ruling
NC, the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism,
CPN-UML) and the Nepal Sadbhavana Party, said a notice issued by
the king's Principal Press Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
As agreed upon by the parties, the coalition government, the
sixth since the mid-term polls in November 1994. is responsible
for conducting free, fair and impartial elections to be held by
March/April 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached Sunday between the NC and the
CPN-UML, the two powers in the parliament, other parties
represented in the parliament would be included in the new
cabinet, which would be small in size.
</P>
<P>
The faction of the National Democratic Party (RPP) led by
former Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand might join the
coalition as its leaders have said they were awaiting formal
invitation.
</P>
<P>
The RPP (Chand), which has eight seats in the 205-member Lower
House of Parliament, was involved in registering on Sunday a
no-confidence motion against the NC government.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) led in
moving the censure motion after pulling out of the
three-and-half-a-month coalition with the NC on December 10.
</P>
<P>
It alleged that the NC had failed to implement the agreements
reached with it and other left parties in August.
</P>
<P>
Following the new round of political turmoil, the main
opposition CPN-UML and other parties held that elections were the
only way out. The CPN-UML demanded a national government for
holding free, fair and impartial elections.
</P>
<P>
The mid-term polls in November 1994 produced a hung parliament
where no single party holds a majority.
</P>
<P>
On December 11, Koirala made a recommendation to the Royal
Palace for the dissolution of the parliament for fresh polls on
March 31, 1999, which was followed by a submission of 62 MPs from
the CPN-ML and its supporters calling for a special parliament
session to discuss their planned censure motion against the
government.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra had decided to call a special session of the
parliament on Thursday as petitioned by the 62 lawmakers and
CPN-ML supporters.
</P>
<P>
But Koirala resigned Monday under the agreement reached with
the CPN-UML to pave the way for the formation of a new coalition,
making the censure motion targetless.
</P>
<P>
Koirala told a press conference here Wednesday afternoon that
the special parliament session will go ahead as scheduled because
it is a constitutional exercise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
