<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Passes Laws on 1999 Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican parliament
Tuesday passed a new electoral law and some regulations
concerning the National Electoral Commission, which has provided
the legal basis for the general elections to be held in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The electoral law stipulates that the president and parliament
members are to be elected by Mozambican citizens in a direct,
secret, fair and general vote, local daily Noticias reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It has a special article on the supervision of voting and
punishment of possible mal-practice.
</P>
<P>
Different from the 1994 elections, the new law also offers
opportunities for Mozambican citizens living abroad to take part
in the general elections.
</P>
<P>
The number of members of the National Electoral Commission is
to be increased from present nine to 17, with the chairman of the
commission to be appointed by the president and two vice-chairmen
to be appointed by the speaker of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The electoral law has come out of 15-day discussion on a
proposal by a joint group which consists of the ruling Mozambican
Liberation Front (Frelimo), the biggest opposition party of
Mozambican National Resistance (Renamo) and the Democratic Union.
</P>
<P>
About 240 of the 250-member parliament were present at the
voting of the electoral law Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
