<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Govt Should Retain 40% Shares of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government should
hold on 40 percent of shares of companies to be privatized to
safeguard the national interest, the New Nigerian Wednesday
quoted a senior business official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Buba Bajoga, Managing Director of Nigerian Telecommunications
Limited (NITEL), told the paper that if the experience of
collapsed private banks was anything to go by, it was imperative
that the government should control substantial shares in NITEL.
</P>
<P>
He described the telecommunications industry as strategic and
sensitive, saying that such an industry could not be left
entirely in the hands of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Bajoga stressed that the government needed to be very cautious
in privatizing such a strategic industry, adding that this was
the case even in countries that were relatively more advanced
than Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Only 30 percent shares of the telecommunications industry are
controlled by the private sector in South Africa while in France
and Germany, 40 percent are in private hands, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Under Nigeria's planned privatization program, 40 percent of
the shares will be sold to foreign technical partners and 20
percent to Nigerians while 40 percent will be retained by the
government.
</P>
<P>
Last week, British trade secretary Brian Wilson who paid a
visit to the west African country advised the Nigerian government
to take a second look at its planned retention of 40 percent
shares in the companies earmarked for privatization.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the 40 percent golden share is likely to act as
a deterrent and may lead to the collapse of even the strongest
companies and I think you would like to avoid this."
</P>
<P>
The secretary noted that the 40-40-20 formula should not be
taken as the only way to approach the program, urging the
Nigerian government to be flexible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
