<HEADLINE> Nigerians Condemn Fuel Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian labor unions and
religious groups have condemned the government's decision to
increase the price of petroleum products, according to local
media reports Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general of the National Public Service
Negotiating Council, Sylvester Ejofoh, said Tuesday in Lagos that
the increase "is another invitation to Mr. inflation to come and
ravage Nigerians."
</P>
<P>
The general secretary of the Civil Service Union, Paul Okolo,
described the increase as "outrageous and saddening", adding that
"they have made a very sad Christmas for Nigerians and workers,
in particular."
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to reverse the decision.
</P>
<P>
The Catholic Bishop of Ekiti Diocese, Michael Fagun, said the
increase in the pump price would deepen poverty in the ranks of
the impoverished Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to combat persistent fuel scarcity, the Nigerian
government has recently decided to deregulate the fuel market,
allowing major marketers to decide fuel prices and import
directly.
</P>
<P>
The decision has led to the increase of fuel price from 11
Naira per liter to about 25 Naira per liter (One U.S. Dollar
equals to 86 Naira).  
