<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Kenya's Economic Recovery Lies in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's economy beleaguered
since the multi-party election year of 1997 went in deeper water
throughout 1998, and experts said the outlook into early 1999
remains bleak.
</P>
<P>
Real gross domestic product (GDP) growth fell to 1.6 percent
in the year to July, down from 2.3 percent last year and well
below estimated population growth of 2.5 percent, latest data
from the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) show.
</P>
<P>
"Economic performance is expected to remain depressed into
early 1999" when the global recession is also expected to further
erode prospects for economic recovery by reducing the demand and
depressing the prices of the country's exports, the CBK added.
</P>
<P>
Last week, President Daniel arap Moi told Kenyans to prepare
even harder economic times next year, saying that the recession
would worsen due to economic problems in Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
High interest rates, low investors' confidence and collapsing
infrastructure have strangled the economy this year, while El
Nino-related bad weather has also hampered agricultural
production, especially that of coffee, sugar and horticulture.
</P>
<P>
The CBK also blamed the slower growth on a decline in foreign
aid, labor unrest, huge domestic debts and the delayed effects of
past insecurity and political turmoil due to the elections held
at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
A bomb raid on the U.S. embassy in Nairobi on August 7 killed
over 250 people and caused extensive damage to local businesses.
The Kenyan government estimated the losses hit 500 million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the trouble has been brewing for quite some time in
this east African country, suiting an old Chinese saying -- No
river can freeze three feet deep within one day.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, although enjoying the rare reputation as "the Peace
Oasis in Africa" since its independence in 1963, has staggered in
the economic development, especially after it started democratic
and liberal reforms in early 1990s partly in a desperate bid to
cater for aid money.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of a 205-million-Dollar aid package by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) in mid 1997 shook Kenya with
instant results that investors' confidence plummeted and interest
and foreign exchange rates skyrocketed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Kenya's Economic Recovery Lies in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, this just adds a new one to many vivid examples
showing the vulnerability of the structure-unbalanced Kenyan
economy, mainly propped up by tourism and several cash crops like
tea and coffee.
</P>
<P>
The figures show that Kenya has a foreign debt of 4.9 billion
U.S. Dollars with an annual debt payment of 800 million Dollars,
posing a burden to the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
With debts making up one-third of the annual GDP and civil
servants wages two-third of the government's expenditure, space
for re-investing socio-economic development including education,
health and industry is left very limited, thus seriously
depending on conditional foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the income distribution is the second unbalanced in
the world according to the U.N. data. The 10 percent richest
Kenyans enjoy 47.7 percent of the national incomes while the 10
percent poorest only get 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
What is worsening the situation is corruption, which senior
Kenyan officials repeated in public, has spread "from top to
bottom" of the whole society. Foreign donors now see it as the
largest impediment to the country's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The IMF cites graft and poor governance as key reasons behind
its aid lapse which is expected to last at earliest into mid
1999. The World Bank cut about half of its grant from this year
due to the fact that on average, only three percent of projects
can be underway yearly.
</P>
<P>
President Moi recently declared a war against embezzlement of
public funds and urged all public servants to have a duty and
moral obligation to serve the public with utmost honesty.
</P>
<P>
Throughout 1998, the government has been successful in
carrying out tight policies to curb inflation, the public
spending and interest rates while improving infrastructure,
especially roads, and expanding markets in east and southern
Africa.
</P>
<P>
In addition, various economic sectors such as trade,
industrial development and telecommunications are taking measures
to speed up their reform and liberalization processes so as to
raise their efficiency and lure domestic and foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
But local analysts said they are afraid that lack of good
results from the anti-graft campaign will frustrate governmental
morals and efforts to recover investors' confidence, as in the
IMF case, and finally to kill efforts to revamp the economy.
</P>
<P>
Hope lies in deepened reforms, they said, Kenya should take
bolder political and economic measures to crack down on
corruption, to reshape the socio-economic system, to boost
manufacturing and narrow the gap between the rich and the poor,
so as to accumulate needed economic momentum.
</P>
<P>
As a new millennium is approaching, it is high time that Kenya
should make urgent efforts to embark on a sound development cycle
to realize a stable and sustainable economic growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
