<HEADLINE> Dar Stock Exchange Turnover Rises Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Dar es Salaam Stock
Exchange (DSE) Wednesday recorded a turnover of 15.2 million
Shillings (about 22,355 U.S. Dollars), a sharp increase of 134
percent over last week.
</P>
<P>
A total of 25,040 shares were traded in 12 deals at the
exchange, the sole one in Tanzania, said Robert C. Mathu, a DSE
technical advisor.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania Oxygen Limited (TOL) counter remained active as
5,000 shares were traded in only one deal at 390 Shillings per
share (about 665 Shillings equal to one U.S. Dollar).
</P>
<P>
The reason for the active transactions is that share-holders
have heard the news that the management of the loss-making TOL is
negotiating with strategic investors, Emmanuel Nyalali, the DSE
systems and operation official told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania Breweries Limited (TBL) shares opened high at 670
Shillings per share and closed lower at 630 Shillings per share,
a drop of 4.8 percent from last week's closing price of 660
Shillings per share, said a statement issued by the DSE.
</P>
<P>
At the close of the session, 200 TOL shares were on bid at 385
Shillings per share, while 4,000 shares were on offer at 390
Shillings per share and 200 others at 400 Shillings per share,
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
TBL, a joint venture between the government and a South
African company, had 12,210 shares on offer at 650 Shillings and
680 Shillings per share with no outstanding bids as the session
closed, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Dar es Salaam Stock Exchange opens once a week, on
Wednesdays, since only two companies have been listed so far.
</P>
<P>
TOL Limited, a leading manufacturer and distributor of
industrial and medical gases, was the first public company listed
on the stock exchange in the first half of the year. TBL came on
board in August to make the shares market more lively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
