<HEADLINE> China Drafts Tough Copyright Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China intends to tighten up
its copyright laws and a draft amendment outlining the moves, and
a tough new stance on piracy was submitted to the country's top
legislative body today.
</P>
<P>
In recent years China has signed many international treaties
and promised to crack down on offenders, who it believes are
harming the public's and society's interests.
</P>
<P>
With continued economic, scientific and cultural development, a
revision of the existing Copyright Law is essential, said Yu
Youxian, director of the State Press and Publications
Administration and the National Copyright Administration, today at
the sixth meeting of the Standing Committee of the Ninth National
People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
"It is increasingly more important to handle correctly our
international obligations as well as protecting domestic
copyright," Yu added.
</P>
<P>
The amendment lists ten items affecting property rights
including copying, distribution, exhibition, public performance,
broadcasting and translation.
</P>
<P>
The revised law has also put a number of new items under
protection, including data bank information.
</P>
<P>
It includes specific provision for the transfer of copyright
and compensation claims for pirated works.
</P>
<P>
Yu added that the revised law encourages authors to take the
initiative in such incidences and will assist the authorities in
their ongoing battle against the piracy of cultural, artistic and
scientific works.
</P>
<P>
It also protects the copyright of works by foreigners,
according to the international treaties and agreements China has
signed.
</P>
<P>
However, provisions related to issues caused by hi-tech
development, and which are still in controversy internationally,
will not be included in the new draft.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
