<HEADLINE> Yassin Freed From House Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Hamas spiritual leader Sheik
Ahmed Yassin was freed Wednesday by Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) from nearly two months of house arrest in Gaza,
the Voice of Palestine reported.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Hamas (Islamic Resistance Movement), Mahmoud
Zahar, said the group welcomed the PNA's decision to free Yassin.
</P>
<P>
With the lifting of the house arrest, Yassin was expected
to receive a few close associates. During his house arrest, he
was prevented from meeting visitors.
</P>
<P>
Yassin was put under house arrest on October 29, after a Hamas
activist killed himself in an unsuccessful attempt to blow up a
school bus full of Israeli school children in the Gaza Strip. The
attack came only six days after the Israel and the Palestinians
signed the Wye peace accord in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Yassin's house arrest, which deeply angered his followers, was
one of the PNA's strongest steps against Hamas. At one point, in a
leaflet signed by its military wing, Hamas demanded Yasin's
release and made a rare direct threat against PNA Chairman Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Yassin's release drew criticism from the Israeli government.
Moshe Fogel, Director of the Government Press Office, said the
PNA has to decide whether it wants to meet its commitments to
fight Hamas terror and move the peace process forward or turn a
blind eye to the terrorist activities of the Hamas leadership.
</P>
