<HEADLINE> EDS-BRITAIN-MINISTER- UK Trade Minister Quits over House Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- British Trade Secretary Peter
Mandelson has resigned after it was revealed Monday that he
borrowed 373,000 pounds (about 620,000 U.S. dollars) from
Paymaster General Geoffrey Robinson.
</P>
<P>
His resignation was announced by Cabinet Minister Jack
Cunningham. The minister told an independent television station
on Wednesday that Mandelson had failed to declare a loan given to
him by Robinson, who is reportedly a self-made millionaire.
</P>
<P>
Mandelson used the loan to buy a house in London's fashionable
Notting Hill area two years ago, while the Labor Party was in
opposition.
</P>
<P>
The row gained impetus because the trade secretary's
department is now investigating alleged irregularities in
Robinson's business dealings.
</P>
<P>
Conservative leader William Hague wrote to Prime Minister Tony
Blair claiming that Mandelson was clearly in breach of
parliamentary rules on conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
Blair on Tuesday defended Mandelson after the latter admitted
receiving the secret loan from Paymaster Robinson.
</P>
<P>
Mandelson has repeatedly stated that he did nothing wrong and
there was no conflict of interest involved.
</P>
<P>
Mandelson is the third minister in Blair's government to
resign after Ron Davies and Frank Field resigned earlier this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
