<HEADLINE> China Auto Market Continues to Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Production and sales of autos
in China grew for the third consecutive month in November,
according to industry analysts, a trend they say will continue in
1999.
</P>
<P>
China turned out 157,000 autos in the month and sales reached
142,000, which are higher levels of achievement than in the first
eleven months of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Automotive Industry Development Research Institute (AIDRI)
attributes the rise to the confidence of manufacturers who
increased output in the last few months. This, they say, led to an
unprecedented simultaneous increase in sales.
</P>
<P>
In January-November this year, China turned out a total of
1.487 million autos with sales of 1.43 million.
</P>
<P>
However, the actual growth rate in both production and sales
was still not as high as the same period last year, by four
percent and five percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
An AIDRI spokesman explained that this could be a result of the
government's restructuring of many sectors which had reduced
demand for company cars, and that measures introduced to expand
the private car market are still to have any marked impact.
</P>
<P>
A general economic slowing down and a sluggish consumer market
also factored in the car market's results.
</P>
<P>
However, he did point out that the government's moves to
stimulate the economy have begun to have an effect on the auto
industry generally. The sales of heavy duty trucks, for example,
has shown a two digit increase.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
