<HEADLINE> Sudanese Parliament Rejects Presidential Call </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Sudan's National Assembly
(parliament) rejected a presidential call for it to accept the
resignation of Hassan Abdulla Al Turabi as the parliament speaker.
</P>
<P>
The presidential message called on the legislature to accept
Turabi's resignation, which was submitted early this month, so
that he could work full time as secretary general of the National
Congress, effectively the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
The National Congress is the successor to the ruling National
Islamic Front.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's "Al Rai Al Akhar" daily said the assembly held a
closed-door meeting Tuesday to discuss the message delivered by
First Vice President Ali Osman Mohamed Taha, but failed to reach a
consensus.
</P>
<P>
Some assembly members said that the resignation of Turabi, who
was considered the most influential person in Sudanese government,
would undermine the assembly, pointing out that the resignation
had already given rise to the emergence of contending blocs.
</P>
<P>
Recently, an advisory body of the National Congress held a
meeting chaired by Sudanese President Omar Bashir during which ten
members submitted a note calling for the establishment of a
leadership bureau headed by Bashir.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe the note aims at degrading the role of
Islamic fundamentalist Turabi as the congress chief as well as
promoting Bashir's role.
</P>
<P>
Bashir dissolved all political parties after he seized power in
a 1989 military coup. He signed a bill early December to legalize
political parties, which will come into effect on January 1,
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
