<HEADLINE> Protecting Rights of Migrant People in China's Three Gorges Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The city of Chongqing is
giving priority to the rights of a million people who have to be
moved from the area of the Three Gorges Dam project.
</P>
<P>
These people face problems that have never had to be dealt with
before and require new measures related to economic, civil and
criminal laws.
</P>
<P>
Local officials complain that, apart from some regional
regulations, there is not a single law dealing with problems of
resettled people. The city's Intermediary People's Court has had
an increasing number of civil and criminal cases since the
relocation program started in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Some legal scholars have warned that law enforcement is
especially important in guaranteeing public security during the
relocation process. They say that most of them are from rural
areas and are far from well-off and the government needs to
increase supervision of the state-subsidized fund to make sure it
goes to the right places. 
</P>
