<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Implement New Agriculture Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will implement
its Third National Agriculture Policy (NAP3) approved by the
cabinet Wednesday over a 13-year period until 2010, Agriculture
Minister Sulaiman Daud announced at a press conference here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new policy's main objective is maximizing income through
optimum use of agricultural resources by introducing two
approaches, namely agroforestry and a product-based strategy, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The new policy spells out new approaches to deal with current
challenges facing the agriculture sector and strategies to tackle
inflation.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet at its weekly meeting Wednesday also endorsed the
Agriculture Action Plan which spells out the commitment required
of all quarters to realizing the strategies laid down in the
policy, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said an estimated investment of 32 billion ringgit (8.42
billion U.S. dollars), of which 21 billion ringgit (5.53 billion
dollars) by the private sector and 11 billion ringgit (about 2.89
billion dollars) by the public sector, would be required to
implement the policy strategies.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the new dual approach could deal with the
present challenges of ensuring enough supply of nutritious and
safe food at reasonable costs and other challenges facing the
agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
He said that on the product-based approach, the policy
emphasized the need to identify products and main markets based on
demand, market potentials and customer preference.
</P>
<P>
Sulaiman said the strategies for boosting local food production
include concentration on cost-effective food products such as
fisheries, fruits and vegetables, zoning of areas specifically for
food production and intensified research and development to
increase output.
</P>
<P>
In promoting agricultural growth and new high-value industries,
the NAP3 would focus on developing biotechnological and natural
chemical products, oil-palm biomass products, horticulture and
ornamental fishes, he said.
</P>
<P>
The NAP3 encourages the private sector to practice hi-tech
farming methods through the development of agro-technology parks.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the NAP3 would lead the country's agriculture
sector into commercialized farming, with emphasis on food
production, resource-based industries and new industries such as
biotechnology and natural chemical and oil palm biomass products.
</P>
</TEXT>
