<HEADLINE> Tudjman Calls For Concerted Efforts Towards Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Croatian President Franjo
Tudjman on Tuesday called on the three ethnic groups of Serbs,
Croats and Muslims in Bosnia to make concerted efforts towards
peaceful co-existence.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony for the construction of the
Sava River Bridge, Tudjman said the bridge when finished would not
only serve as an economic linkage among the three groups, but also
enhance their communications.
</P>
<P>
The Sava bridge across Croatia and Bosnia was destroyed in 1992
when wars broke out in the former Yugoslav region, and would be
restored with a 6.5 million dollars loan from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
This signaled that Bosnia-Herzegovina had entered a stage of
peaceful coexistence and progress, Tudjman said.
</P>
<P>
He then stressed that the Washington Agreement, Dayton Peace
Accord and the Croatia-Bosnia accord on establishing special
relations had paved the way for a permanent resolution to the
conflicts in the region.
</P>
<P>
With these documents implemented, people in the region could
live peacefully together and refugees return to places where
life would be safe and free, Tudjman said.
</P>
<P>
The three ethnic groups should seek pragmatic solutions to
their problems, which could serve their interests, the
president said. Meanwhile, the international community should not
pursue "such an unreasonable and ambiguous idea as establishing
some kind of a unified Bosnia country," he added, and history had
disproved the feasibility of such an idea.
</P>
<P>
The reality was, Tudjman said, the three groups were now living
in Bosnia and they should find a permanent solution that could let
them live together free from conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
