<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Time Catches Up With Ancient Uygur Tribe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- When China laid down laws to
protect wildlife, the impact on communities such as the descendants
of the Loulan Tribe who had traditionally been hunters and
fishermen was dramatic.
</P>
<P>
They had lived and prospered along the legendary "Silk Road"
for more than 2,000 years, but gradually had been forced to change
their lifestyles with farming and animal husbandry becoming more
common activities in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
But the real changes only began in the 1970s and 96 year old
Ismail, who lives in Awat Village close to Lop Nur Lake to the
southeast of Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, is one of the few
people left alive who can recall his youth, when he was taught to
fish in a canoe and hunt for food.
</P>
<P>
Today, canoes are no longer in use and younger generations in
his village have lost the skills of hunting and fishing. His own
canoe is now used as a trough to feed horses.
</P>
<P>
The Lop Nur people tried to continue the lifestyle enjoyed by
their forefathers for thousands of years but 1980 was a watershed
for them when the new laws were introduced.
</P>
<P>
Shotguns were confiscated by the government and instead the
villagers were allocated plots of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Since that time more than 200 households in Awat have taken to
planting cotton and per-capita farmland has reached half a
hectare, much higher than the country's average.
</P>
<P>
The 34 year old village chief, Ahmad Abdul, proudly even
reveals that labor saving machinery is now bringing in high yields
from the cotton fields. "After over a dozen years of development
we have realized the benefits." he said.
</P>
<P>
Tractors and trucks loaded with cotton are now the
most-commonly seen vehicles in Awat while the old ways of making a
living, fishing and hunting, are merely distant history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
