<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Tighten Up Its Contract Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese legislators drawing up
the draft Contract Law have decided against introducing elements
which would have permitted contractors to challenge details of the
contract, and even have it annulled.
</P>
<P>
In the previous draft contactors would have the right to alter
or abandon their signed agreements if some unpredictable changes
in national policies or the social and economic climate meant they
would suffer losses.
</P>
<P>
Gu Angran, vice-chairman of the Law Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), gave a briefing on the amendment today at
the on-going sixth meeting of the Ninth NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
He referred to the two controversial opinions on the amendment,
saying that some people believe that by retaining those sections
of the draft would affect the real status of contracts, making
them almost worthless.
</P>
<P>
There are those, however, who maintain that such clauses would
be helpful in disputes between contractors, as courts would be
unable to legislate without appropriate regulations.
</P>
<P>
Taking the two points of view into account, the NPC Law
Committee decided to scrap the clauses, insisting that business
risks cannot be cushioned in such a way because of economic or
social changes.
</P>
<P>
Economists have welcomed the new amendment and said that this
indicates the determination of legislators to maintain a stable
national economic policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Greets Its Asiad Delegation Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese vice-primier Li
Lanqing welcomed the Chinese Asian Games delegation in the Great
Hall of the People on Wednesday after they retained the
domination in the medal standings at the regional Olympic-style
gala in Bangkok, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Li, on behalf of the Chinese government, congratulated the
athletes' victories and hailed their successful efforts in
fighting against the doping during the 15-day Games.
</P>
<P>
China sent more than 800 athletes to the Bangkok Games but no
one has tested positive so far.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese athletes captured 129 gold medals, in which 68
percent were taken by the newcomers. Arch-rivals South Korea took
65 and Japan 52.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the Bangkok Games as the mid-term exam, China
already set its eyes at the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
"The end of Asian Games means the beginning of the 2000
Olympics," said Kong Linghui, the men's table-tennis runner-up.
</P>
</TEXT>
