<HEADLINE> China Regrets Verdict of Japanese Court: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China has expressed surprise
and regret over the verdict issued by the Tokyo Court of Japan in
the case of the diary of Shiro Azuma, a former Japanese soldier
who witnessed the infamous "Nanking Massacre" in December 1937,
said Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao here today.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the verdict, which ruled in favor of those
named in the diary as among the Japanese who took part in the
massacre, Zhu said the court's decision ignored the facts of the
history.
</P>
<P>
The war of aggression against China launched by Japanese
militarists in the past brought great sufferings to the Chinese
people, Zhu said, adding that the extremely tragic "Nanking
Massacre" was only one of the atrocities committed by the Japanese
Army in China.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that any action attempting to refute this
historical fact is in vein, and will be strongly condemned by all
people with a sense of justice including the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
"We urge the Japanese side to face up to history and respect
reality, and learn from the past in order to avoid any similar
tragedies from occurring in the future.  
</P>
