<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Makes Big Strides in Reform of State Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Though still facing tough
problems, Shanghai, China's leading industrial city, has made
remarkable progress in restructuring its state-owned enterprises
over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
The output value of local state-owned industrial enterprises
had grown 250 percent over the 1978 figure, to top 281.6 billion
yuan last year, accounting for 52.5 percent of the city's total
industrial output value.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, their gross profits had reached 34.67 billion yuan,
2.3 times the 1978 figure, making up 67.6 percent of the total of
the city's manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
Since 1978, Shanghai has replaced government-set production
quotas for enterprises with a market-oriented system, allowing
state firms to operate as independent entities.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, more than 900 state companies were
merged and another 86 went bankrupt in Shanghai, while an
increasing number of competitive enterprises were formed.
</P>
<P>
The city has also introduced a market-oriented employment
system for state enterprises to let job seekers compete with one
another.
</P>
<P>
As the number of layoffs rises with the reforms, the city
government has set up many re-employment centers in addition to
some 60 labor markets, which have helped the majority of the
city's 1.4 million redundant workers, some 1.19 million, find new
jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
