<HEADLINE> National People's Congress Discusses Wide-ranging Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A bill on the legal status
of the courts and procuratorates attached to the Xinjiang
Production and Construction Corps was tabled during today's sixth
meeting of the National People's Congress (NPC) Standing
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme People's Court and the Supreme People's
Procuratorate explained that clearly defining the legal status of
related judicial departments will promote economic development,
help maintain social stability and strengthen the unity of various
ethnic groups in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Courts and procuratorates under the Xinjiang Production and
Construction Corps were established in the 1950s, but were
disbanded in 1975 following disbandment of the corps. Related
departments were reinstated in 1984.
</P>
<P>
Various courts and procuratorates attached to the corps have
not only performed their trials duties and legal supervision over
the past 14 years, but have also played an important role in
regional construction and maintaining social stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
