<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Gives Grant for Prostate Cancer Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The federal government
Wednesday announced a 900,000-Australian dollar (558,000 U.S.
dollars) grant for a pre-clinical research project on a new
anti-prostate cancer treatment that may avoid the side-effects of
surgery and radiotherapy.
</P>
<P>
The researchers of the project are from the leading
pharmaceutical company F H Faulding &AMP; Co. Ltd. and the
government's Molecular Science and Oncology Research Center.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Michael Wooldridge, while announcing the grant,
said prostate cancer is the second largest cause of cancer deaths
among Australian men, claiming 2,500 lives annually, the
Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
"This prostate cancer research offers real hope for Australian
men, particularly those who develop a form of the disease which
cannot be treated at present," Wooldridge said.
</P>
<P>
Under the revolutionary treatment, genes will be delivered
direct into prostate cancer cells to stimulate the production of
an enzyme, which in turn activates anti-cancer drugs.
</P>
<P>
Researchers said the treatment, which is expected to go into
human clinical trials in two years' time, should be more effective
than current approaches because it will specifically target the
cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
Faulding Chief Executive Officer Ed Tweddell said the gene
treatment is a novel approach which might be used in the fight
against other forms of cancer.
</P>
<P>
The treatment could avoid the need for surgery, radiotherapy
and the use of hormone drugs, which have unpleasant side-effects
such as impotence and incontinence in some cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
