<HEADLINE> China to Spend 2.5 Billion Yuan For Basic Research Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China will spend 2.5 billion
yuan (300 million U.S. dollars) over the next five years for basic
research programs.
</P>
<P>
Deng Nan, vice minister of science, announced at a news
conference here today that the first group of 15 basic research
programs will be devoted to the fields including agriculture,
energy, information, resources and environment, population and
health, and new materials.
</P>
<P>
She said China has selected research programs that are of great
significance for social and economic development.
</P>
<P>
The 15 basic research programs include the application of
high-efficiency optical energy in agriculture, the search for
crop genes for developing future crop seeds, the forecasting of
strong earthquakes and other natural disasters, high-performance
software, the incidence and growth of tumors, and new iron and
steel materials.
</P>
<P>
She said implementation of the programs are of great importance
for guaranteeing the country's social and economic development
during the first 10 years of the next century.
</P>
<P>
An official with the China Seismological Bureau said his bureau
will announce the implementation of plans to develop quake
prediction programs via the Internet, and is ready to attract
leading scientists at home and abroad for this effort.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Lilan, minister of science and technology, stressed the
need to launch major basic-research programs with Chinese
characteristics and a pioneering spirit. 
</P>
