<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Intensify Implementation of Military Service Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The newly modified draft of
the Military Service Law, which has been submitted to the sixth
meeting of the Standing Committee of the ninth National People's
Congress (NPC), includes a series of measures on the punishment of
those who refuse to perform their military service.
</P>
<P>
These measures which aim to ensure the smooth implementation of
the Military Service Law are as follows: the local government has
the right to compel those people to perform their military
service, or they will be fined; and they are not allowed to apply
for jobs in official organizations and state-owned enterprises, or
to further their studies either at home or abroad, for two years.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Keyu, vice-chairman of the Law Committee of the NPC, said
the new draft law has been modified because many members of the
Standing Committee thought there should be an exact period for the
punishment.
</P>
<P>
He said that the draft adds that local governments on
the county level have the right to fine those enterprises who hire
soldiers who have left the army without permission, and they
may even be subject to criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
The draft provides that soldiers will be given preferential
treatment when they apply for a job at official organizations or
continue their studies after they finish their military
service, and local government are allowed to work out other
preferential measures based on their own conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0109 </DOCNO>
