<HEADLINE> Taxis in Shanghai to Use liquefied Petroleum and Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai plans to fix special
devices onto its 4,100 taxis within four years, using liquefied
petroleum and natural gas from the East China Sea.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government believes that such devices will help
reduce air pollution and has already started to change the fuel
structure of buses and taxis since 1997, in addition to the
measures to stop using leaded petroleum and fixing purification
for the vehicleS emission system.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has already built up five gas stations
and fixed 3,000 taxis with devices using liquefied petroleum and
gas by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Survey showed that such devices may help reduce the carbon
monoxide by 86 percent in the emission of vehicles, the carbon
dioxide by 33 percent, and the hydrocarbon and nitrogen oxide, by
one-forth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
