<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fog Causes Closure of Airport in Indian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Air traffic has come to a
halt in New Delhi as thick fog enveloping the Indian capital for
more than a week forced the closure of the airport Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
No flight has taken off or landed since 23:30 local time
Tuesday due to near zero visibility, airport sources said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 Delhi-bound passengers were stranded at Mumbai
airport following the closure of Delhi airport.
</P>
<P>
Railway traffic in North India was also affected by the fog
with most of the trains passing through Delhi delayed.
</P>
<P>
Government officials and workers, company employees and school
children were among the worst affected with vehicles moving at a
snail's pace in the city which has a population of more 10
million.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said the closure of the airport was due to the
lack of a modern landing system, which can help overcome the
limitation caused by fog and help aircraft land when the
visibility is zero.
</P>
<P>
All flights, domestic and international, have been affected,
with nearly 40 percent of Indian Airlines flights being hit by
cancellations and delays for a week.
</P>
<P>
The closure will add more financial burden on Air India and
India Airlines which already lost more than 30 million U.S.
dollars in the first half of the current financial year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
