<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tomb of Ancient Knight Discovered in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHOT, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A tomb more than 1,000 years
old containing a large coffin and many bows, arrows and spears has
been discovered in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
An archeological report said the tomb also held the remains of
a man wearing linen and silk dresses and lying beside a 1.4
meter-long spear, a 1.5-meter-long bow, and an arrow bag and
several arrows, with a wooden saddle under his head.
</P>
<P>
According to his posture, archeologists believe that when he
was placed into the coffin he probably had a bow in hands and
an arrow bag on his back, as though he were still alive and
prepared for the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
The unearthed items also include wooden chopsticks and
plates. Archeologists believe their style is that of the Tang
Dynasty (618-917), when nomadic tribes in north China already had
extensive contact with people living in the central plains.
</P>
<P>
The nationality of the tomb's occupant remains a
mystery, according to archeologists, adding that further
studies will be pursued.
</P>
<P>
Nine other tombs dating back to the same era have also been
discovered in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
