<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislature Deliberates International Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The National People's Congress
(NPC) Standing Committee, China's legislature, today deliberated
an international convention on the Minimum Age for Employment
formulated by the International Labor Organization (ILO).
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji introduced a proposal at the sixth meeting
of NPC Standing Committee concerning the Convention on the Minimum
Age for Employment. The proposal states that the convention does
not contradict Chinese law and thus ratification will be in the
best interests of the nation.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zuoji, minister of Labor and Social Security, explained
the proposal to members of the nation's top legislative body.
</P>
<P>
The convention stipulates that the minimum age for employment
for youngsters in countries with underdeveloped economies and low
education should be above 14 years of age, with age in other
countries set at 15, according to Zhang. He pointed out that
Chinese law currently stipulates the minimum age at 16.
</P>
<P>
The convention shows that the international community pays
close attention to the ban of use of child labor, according to
Zhang.
</P>
<P>
China is carefully considering joining the convention to
eliminate the employment of child labor.
</P>
<P>
However, the convention will not apply to the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) before the Chinese government
makes a separate announcement.
</P>
<P>
A total of 59 ILO members had ratified the convention by the
end of last year. The convention was formulated in 1973 and took
effect in 1976.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
