<HEADLINE> Japan Donates Polio Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government
recently donated 30 million vaccine units valued at 700,000 US
dollars to reinforce China's efforts to eradicate polio.
</P>
<P>
Japan has donated a total of 150 million units over the past
eight years, according Nobuyuki Sugimoto, minister of the Japanese
Embassy in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
He said the concerted Sino-Japanese effort to battle polio
commenced in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Japan International Cooperation Agency (JICA) also sent
experts and equipment to China to establish polio monitoring
systems and laboratory networks. Related efforts are currently
being carried out in eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
Health departments will initiate a new vaccination campaign on
January 5 as part of an effort to polio eradication goals for the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"While virus strains of polio have not been detected in China
since 1994, we must not be complacent in terms of
vaccinations since cases of polio are still prevalent in various
neighboring countries, with weak prevention efforts in some
areas," according to Wang Zhao, director of the Disease Control
Department of the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
China reported between 40,000-50,000 polio cases, including a
number of deaths, each year before the government introduced the
national vaccination campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
