<HEADLINE> Probe Shows Soeharto Could Be Suspect of Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Attorney General
Andi M. Ghalib said Wednesday preliminary results of the ongoing
probe of the alleged ill-gotten wealth of former senior officials
indicate that former president Soeharto could become a suspect in
a corruption case.
</P>
<P>
"Based on the preliminary results, we see such indication.
However, we have to be careful, we have to do some
cross-checking," Ghalib told reporters before joining a cabinet
meeting here.
</P>
<P>
He said his office has summoned former senior officials,
including former ministers, to cross-check Soeharto's statements.
</P>
<P>
The questioning covered the national car company PT Timor Putra
National, which received unprecedented preferential treatment,
including tax exemptions and large sums of low-interest loans.
</P>
<P>
Ghalib called on the people to be patient and show wisdom in
waiting for the results of the investigations.
</P>
<P>
"There is no need to become emotional," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked if Soeharto will be summoned again, he said, "After
all the questionings are completed, we will summon him again."
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was forced to step down on May 21 amid the country's
worst political and economic crisis in decades. He is accused of
corruption and abuse of power during his 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
On December 9, the former president was questioned at Jakarta's
Higher Prosecutors Office and was asked 43 questions on his
alleged corrupt, collusive and nepotistic practices during his
rule. 
</P>
