<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Declining Growth Rate For Farmers' Income Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The slowdown in income growth
for Chinese farmers is expected to continue in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the average per capita net income this year is
expected to increase by three percent on the 1997 level.
</P>
<P>
"The continuing slow growth in rural income levels represents a
prominent problem China faces in the new stage of agricultural
development," according to Wan Baorui, vice minister of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Farmers have enjoyed constantly improving living standards
since 1980, with statistics showing that the average per capita
net income for Chinese farmers hit 2,090 yuan in 1997, a 3.4-fold
rise on the figure for two decades ago when allowing for price
hikes.
</P>
<P>
However, the slowdown in income increases has created a
bottleneck hindering the country's agricultural development, said
Wan.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the slowdown to the oversupply of certain farm
products, ailing rural enterprises and devastating summer flooding
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Wan pointed out that the government has attached great
importance to raising the income of farmers by stabilizing the
acreage of land dedicated to grain production, optimizing the
rural economic structure and accelerating the introduction of
agricultural technological.
</P>
<P>
"We must ease burdens on farmers and eliminate irrational
costs, according to Wan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
