<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak, Tajikistan Call for End to Foreign Interference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and Tajikistan have
called for end to foreign interference in the Afghan issue and
said "the Afghans should be allowed to sit together to find a
solution to the crisis themselves."
</P>
<P>
The appeal came Wednesday during the meeting between visiting
Tajik Foreign Minister Talbak Nazarov and his Pakistani
counterpart Sartaj Aziz.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Foreign Ministry said that "the two
sides reiterated their commitment to the early establishment of
durable peace in Afghanistan and agreed to intensify their efforts
towards this end both bilaterally as well as through the `Six plus
Two' mechanism."
</P>
<P>
Nazarov arrived here Tuesday night on a two-day visit for talks
with Pakistani officials on the Afghan issue. Their discussion
Wednesday covered the entire range of bilateral relations and
focused in particular on the Afghan situation.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of Pakistan and Tajikistan emphasized
that there should be end to outside interference to the Afghan
issue and supply of arms in Afghanistan without which durable
peace would not be possible.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers agreed that the restoration of peace
and stability in Afghanistan was of utmost importance and would
not only benefit the Afghans but would also open up enormous
possibilities for the development of the entire region.
</P>
<P>
The Afghans should be allowed to sit together to find a
solution to the long-running Afghan crisis themselves, they said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers also said that the "Six plus Two"
(Afghanistan's six immediate neighbors plus Russia and the U.S.)
should play a supporting role to achieve peace in Afghanistan, and
Pakistan and Tajikistan should work together to achieve these
objectives.
</P>
<P>
Nazarov's visit is part of a series of intensified bilateral
consultations between Pakistan and countries bordering
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Siddique Khan
Kanju visited four Central Asian Republics in August and November
this year, and U.N. Special Envoy on the Afghan issue Lakhdar
Brahimi made a two-day visit to Pakistan early this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
