<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Maintains Stable Currency (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PBOC Governor Dai Xianglong has consistently stressed the solid
foundation for a stable currency. For example, the Chinese economy
continues to enjoy sustained healthy development, with foreign
exchange reserves reaching 143.7 billion US dollars by the end of
October.
</P>
<P>
Dai said the figure continues to rise along with the increasing
trade surplus, balanced international payments, and flexible
exchange rate system based on market supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
A Beijing University Research Center report on the Chinese
economy notes that the stability of the yuan has helped maintain
the confidence of overseas investors, effectively reduced
financial risks on the domestic front and helped ensure the
stability of the Hong Kong dollar peg to the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
China's efforts to maintain the stability of the yuan have also
 improved the nation's status in the international
community. China's contributions to stablizing both the regional
and global economies have been acknowledged, and many foreign
government leaders have publically expressed their appreciation
and gratitude to the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
Economist Liu Guangcan noted the rationality of the current
yuan exchange rate when taking China's current accounts surplus in
recent years into consideration, as well as various other
important factors such as the foreign trade surplus, influx of
capital, inflation rate and money supply.
</P>
<P>
However, a point well worth noting is that China has maintained
a stable currency in spite of intense pressure from the Asian
financial crisis. Some people question China's ability to maintain
the stability of the yuan. Many experts dismiss the questions and
stress that China indeed has the ability to honor its pledge.
</P>
<P>
Noted economist Li Boxi pointed out that maintaining the
stability of the yuan has not been accomplished without certain
costs. The effort did however create a stable macroeconomic
environment for ensuring sustained economic growth. The the basic
factors underlining the stability of the yuan will carry over into
1999. No one should worry about the continued stability of the
currency.
</P>
<P>
Liu noted that the State Administration of Foreign Exchange
recently adopted a series of effective measures to verify the
authenticity of current accounts trade and reinforce foreign
exchange management under capital accounts. The fact that China
has cracked down firmly on illegal practices in the foreign
exchange sector will be beneficial for maintaining the stability
of the yuan exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
"Maintaining a stable yuan exchange rate and gradually
introducing a fully convertible currency represent long-term
targets for reform of the foreign exchange system," according to
Dai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
