<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koirala Wins Support to Form New Govt in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister of Nepal's
caretaker government Girija Prasad Koirala said here Wednesday
that he has won the support of 135 members in the Lower House of
Parliament, much more than needed to stake claim to power.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that 84 lawmakers from his Nepali
Congress (NC), 48 from the Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) and three from the Nepal Sadbhavana
Party had signed the letter supporting him to lead the new
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra is expected to name Koirala Wednesday to form a
new coalition.
</P>
<P>
Koirala said that the cabinet will be announced after the new
government wins a confidence vote in the 205-seat Lower House.
</P>
<P>
He said that given the terrorist activities and the fluid
political situation in the country, there is no other alternative
to an all-party government for conducting free, fair and impartial
elections.
</P>
<P>
He said that fresh polls should be held by March/April 1999.
</P>
<P>
The political turmoil erupted when the Communist Party of Nepal
(Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) pulled out on December 10 after sharing
power with the NC for three and a half months.
</P>
<P>
It alleged that the NC had failed to enforce the agreements
reached with it and other left parties in August.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-ML and its supporters registered Sunday a no-confidence
motion against the NC government.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra had decided to call a special session of
parliament on Thursday as petitioned by the lawmakers of the
CPN-ML and its supporters.
</P>
<P>
But Koirala resigned Monday under an agreement with the CPN-UML
to make way for the formation of a new coalition to conduct fresh
elections, making the censure motion targetless.
</P>
<P>
Koirala told the press conference that the special parliament
session will be convened as scheduled because it is a
constitutional exercise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
