<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Legislature to Review Eight Draft Laws (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature, the
National People's Congress Standing Committee, began its new
bi-monthly session here today to examine three draft laws on
securities, the military services and a bill proposing the
establishment of a budgetary watchdog in the legislature.
</P>
<P>
The securities law, amendments to the military-service law and
amendments to the penal code concerning foreign-exchange-related
crimes are expected to be adopted in this session, according to an
agenda passed at the meeting today.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, presided over
today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen additional major alterations were made to the draft
securities law to further protect investors from market risks
and set more comprehensive and specific standards for market
operations.
</P>
<P>
The amendments to the military-service law provides further
penalties for refusing to fulfill military-service
obligations.
</P>
<P>
The decision on punishing foreign-currency-related crimes
includes forgers of documents used to illegally obtain foreign
currencies as accomplices of those who actually receive the money,
and metes out even more severe punishment to the forgers.
</P>
<P>
Two other draft laws, the contract law, and the law on
administrative appeals, were re-tabled by the lawmakers today.
</P>
<P>
The latest draft of the contract law cancels the "changes of
national social and economic policy" as a factor for the
possible write-off of contracts, reflecting the lawmakers' wish
that such changes not affecting the execution of economic
contracts will not occur.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also told that in formulating the law on
administrative appeals, the legislature encountered two
"complicated and major" issues: whether government decrees or
policies can be appealed, and whether the highest administrative
body, the State Council, will accept such appeals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
