<HEADLINE> Share Prices Tumble on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Share prices plummeted
sharply on Singapore Stock Market Wednesday driven down by contra
players' bailing-out and U.S. Federal Reserve's decision not to
change interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) lost 27.87 points to
end at 1,384.53 points in thin trading.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover slipped to 109.52 million units worth 159.36
million Singapore dollars (about 92.32 million U.S. dollars).
Falls outnumbered rises by 191 to 46 with 183 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
DBS Land still topped the actives chart of the day with a
turnover of 6.23 million units. ST Cap was the second most heavily
traded stock with a volume of 5.96 million units done. InchMarket
was next with 4.00 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Asean led the gainers of the day as it rose by 40 cents to
finish at 6.50 U.S. dollars. Jurship and OCBC F inched up 10 cents
and closed at 7.30 and 11.50 Singapore dollars respectively. Thai
Pr also gained 10 cents but ended at 4.00 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH 100 led the descent of the day with a
decline of 80 cents to 17.60 Singapore dollars. ABR Hldgs was next
shedding 67.5 cents to close at 0.635 Singapore dollars. DBS F
retreated 60 cents to end at 15.10 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted share prices fell in thin trading from the start
of dealing of the day as contra players bailed out of their
position.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Open Market Committee's decision to leave rates
unchanged also left the market with little inspiration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
