<HEADLINE> China's Legislature to Review Eight Draft Laws (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A draft explanation on the implementation of the Chinese
Nationality Law in Macao after the handover on December 20, 1999,
and amendments to the Copyright Law were submitted today to the
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
On the nationality issue for Macao residence, the draft
explanation proposed "flexible" means, similar to the rules
defined for Hong Kong, but under the premises of China's legal
principles on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The amendments to the Copyright Law call for drastic
strengthening of protection for domestic copyright holders, up to
the level given to foreign copyright holders registered in China.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme People's Court and the Supreme People's
Procuratorate proposed a bill today affirming as a legal entity
the court and prosecution offices of the Xinjiang Production and
Construction Corps.
</P>
<P>
The corps is a unique combination of Party, political, military
and business organizations, charged with the task of agricultural
production and border defense. It has control over its own legal
and administrative affairs.
</P>
<P>
Both the Supreme Court and the Supreme Procuratorate noted that
the courts and prosecution offices inside the corps played a
special role in helping maintain stability in the the corps and in
the whole of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, strengthening
ethnic unity and consolidating border defense.
</P>
<P>
Thus, affirming as a legal entity the courts and prosecution
offices of the corps is necessary for the better performance of its
duties, the lawmakers were told.
</P>
<P>
To step up efforts for effectively overseeing the formulation
and implementation of national budgets, the NPC Standing Committee
chairman and vice chairmen proposed a bill today to the
legislature for setting up a Standing Committee sub-committee, the
Budget Work Committee.
</P>
<P>
The International Labor Organization Convention Concerning
Minimum Age for Admission to Employment, and a consular treaty
with the Canadian government were also brought before the
lawmakers today for examination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
