<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Priority for Energy Development  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China is stepping up its
development of energy reserves in a bid to meet basic energy
demands in the coming century and guarantee rapid economic and
social development.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior official with the State Development
Planning Commission, the country will pay equal attention to the
exploitation of energy resources and energy saving in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
Energy development will focus on power and be based on coal,
along with the vigorous expansion of petroleum, gas and nuclear
power and other new and renewable energy resources, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China will launch a series of strategic
drives in the next century. In the coal sector, the focus of
production will be shifted westward and efforts will be made to
expand the Shenfu and Dongsheng coal fields and improve coal
transportation.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the country will speed up the construction of
terraced hydroelectric power stations in river valleys and the
construction of power stations near coal mines.
</P>
<P>
In developing the petroleum industry, prominence will be given
to oil and gas exploitation in western China and in the
country's offshore areas.
</P>
<P>
In this way, a network of energy-supply bases will come into
being nationwide, with the provinces of Shanxi, Shaanxi,
Heilongjiang and Guizhou and western Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region as the major coal suppliers. The Daqing and Shengli oil
fields will remain the country's main oil suppliers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Priority for Energy Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the official, the upper reaches of the Yellow
River and the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River will
be bases for supplying hydropower nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Along with the development of conventional energy resources,
the country will still pay attention to the development of
geothermal energy, wind energy, solar energy and tidal energy, so
as to optimize the structure of energy consumption.
</P>
<P>
Experts here noted that China will achieve a balance between
supply and demand in energy resources in the early 21st century.
</P>
<P>
They also say that the current net export volume of 30 million
tons of coal will be further expanded in the early 21 century, but
net imports of oil will show no rapid increases.
</P>
<P>
It is projected that in the early 21st century, the total
consumption of the country's unrenewable energy resources will hit
the equivalent of 1.38 billion tons of standard coal, as coal
output reaches 1.45 billion tons.
</P>
<P>
By then, the country's annual production of oil and gas will
top 150 million tons and 25 billion cubic meters,
respectively. Also by that time, the country's major power grids
will be interconnected nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Experts are confident that China's energy production
and reserves will effectively guarantee social and economic
development in the century to come. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
