<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xinhua Correspondent Xu Xingtang

China Maintains Stable Currency (1)
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government stood
firmly by its pledge not to devalue the yuan (Renminbi) in spite
of sharp devaluations in many Asian currencies due to the
financial crisis engulfing the region.
</P>
<P>
The events of the past year prove that China has fulfilled its
promise.
</P>
<P>
The yuan exchange rate to the US dollar remains at the 8.27:1
level in place at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
An even more encouraging aspect centers on the Chinese
government's early December pledge to maintain the stability of
the yuan in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The panic atmosphere sweeping Asia and bordering regions during
the ongoing crisis caused many people to question China's ability
to maintain a stable currency. Facts disproved frequent foreign
media predictions concerning devaluation of the yuan.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that the courage China has exhibited in making the
promise and success in keeping its word have fully demonstrated
the government's confidence and indeed ability to control the
domestic economy. They also point to the government's correct
assessment of both regional and global economic situations, as
well as the appropriateness of the macroeconomic and financial
policies.
</P>
<P>
"Maintaining the stability of the yuan represents a strategy
revolving around the global economy and Asian economies, as well
as China's long-term interests. It is also a promise based on the
nation's economic strength and management capabilities," according
to Liu Mingkang, deputy governor of the People's Bank of China
(PBOC).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Million More Chinese Shake off Poverty This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China helped more than eight
million rural residents escape absolute poverty during 1998, but
nonetheless fell short of its target of providing a better life
for 10 million people.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Agriculture Chen Yaobang today attributed the
shortfall to heavy summer flooding in northeastern and southern
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
He noted that related departments have not as yet determined
the final figure for the year. However, reports from key areas
confirm that at least eight million rural residents have escaped
poverty.
</P>
<P>
Chen said an estimated 40 million rural residents were living
in absolute poverty at the end of 1998, including more than 10
million disabled individuals and people unable to work, who will
obtain social relief funds to shake off poverty.
</P>
<P>
He said China will accelerate poverty relief efforts in
1999. Chen voiced confidence in China's ability to help the
majority of rural residents escape poverty and achieve its goal of
eliminated absolute poverty by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
