<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Twelve Israeli Wounded in Hezbollah Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Twelve civilians in
Israel's northern towns have been confirmed wounded in rocket
attacks Wednesday morning, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that guerrilla groups of Hezbollah, or Party of
God, claimed responsibility for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
Among the wounded, one was moderately injured and the others
were lightly hurt, it added.
</P>
<P>
The attacks came one day after eight Lebanese civilians,
including a woman and her six children, were killed in an Israeli
air strike on suspected guerrilla bases in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The radio said the Israelis along the northern border had been
sent to the bomb shelters Tuesday night after Hezbollah vowed to
avenge what it called a "massacre" of innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a buffer zone in south Lebanon in 1985 after two
invasions, with the claimed aim to prevent cross-border attacks.
Hezbollah and other Lebanese guerrilla groups have been fighting
to end the Israeli occupation of the area, about one tenth of
Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli security cabinet is expected to convene Wednesday
to discuss the escalated conflict in its self-styled security zone
in south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
