<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crash Not Airline Error, Says THAI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Thai Airways International
(THAI) should not be blamed for the air crash earlier this month
which killed 101 people, airline officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The officials defended THAI's flight operations and insisted
they met international safety standards, saying the crash in
southern Thailand was not an error of the airline.
</P>
<P>
The causes of the crash, which happened in heavy rain in
southern Thailand, remained unknown until the flight data recorder
and pilot voice recorder are investigated by Airbus Industries in
Canada next month, according to the officials who refused to be
named.
</P>
<P>
THAI board chairman Mahidol Chantrangkurn said earlier that the
airline would be ready to disclose the causes of accident to the
public when the investigation was complete. The two recorders
would be sent to the aircraft manufacturer on January 2 and
results were expected in mid January.
</P>
<P>
"We ensure safety standards. This is the top priority for the
airline, followed by services, cost cutting and technological
development," said Mahidol.
</P>
<P>
However, Mahidol said that the airline will be required to
verify its operations later. There has been no impact on the
airline and flights remain fully booked on major routes.
</P>
<P>
Transport and Communications Minister Suthep Thuagsuban said
earlier that he wanted the existing board to stay on in order to
continue a privatization plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
