<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Upgrade Water Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has worked out a program
for upgrading barrages and waterways, canals and pumping stations
across the country.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Public Works and Water Resources Mahmoud Abu Zeid
said Tuesday the program is aimed at increasing agricultural
production and rationalizing the use of water in irrigation, the
Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Abu Zeid made the remarks during a ceremony held in al-Menoufia
Governorate to the north of Cairo for laying the foundation stone
of a viaduct across the el-Menoufi Canal.
</P>
<P>
He said the program is estimated to cost 5 billion Egyptian
pounds (1.47 billion U.S. dollars). But he did not say when the
program will be implemented.
</P>
<P>
The official said that his ministry has also started studies on
developing irrigation in the western Nile Delta, especially the
northern Wadi el-Natron, covering 200,000 feddans (84,000
hectares) of land, with a cost of 400 million pounds (118 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the private sector will play a role in
developing irrigation and drainage foundations.
</P>
<P>
Farmers unions have been allowed to operate irrigation
foundations and distribute water in the Delta, the minister said,
adding that the step has resulted in a remarkable increase in the
agricultural production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
