<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Securities Law Being Proposed This Year (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) - A draft of China's
long-awaited securities law is coming up for vote in the last few
days of this year.
</P>
<P>
The new 7-day session of China's top legislature, which started
in Beijing today, will put it to a vote by the end of the session,
according to an agenda that was passed today.
</P>
<P>
The 59-page draft for review by lawmakers has 15 major changes
from a previous version, including prohibition of state-owned
enterprises and banks from speculating in the market and
prohibition of foreign capital from entering the A-share market as
a protection of domestic investors, according to Qiao Xiaoyang,
the vice-chairman of the NPC Law Committee.
</P>
<P>
All the changes are meant to be a bulwark against market risks
and to improve the definition of market operations and increase
the transparency of government market controls, Qiao told the
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
If state-owned enterprises, with their colossal economic
muscle, or banks with their loans are allowed to speculate, they
could easily manipulate the market and further fuel speculation,
he warned, and they would put state assets in serious jeopardy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Securities Law Being Proposed This Year (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Controls on the movement of bank money to the securities market
by the government have been effective in preventing market crises
and should be put into law, the lawmakers were told.
</P>
<P>
The draft also has a two-tier system for brokerages requiring
stock brokers to keep their own trading accounts separate from
those of clients.
</P>
<P>
Qiao says that some brokers have been found to be
misappropriating their clients money for use in their own
accounts, and this is very risky.
</P>
<P>
To defend A-shares from foreign speculation the draft was
changed to read "a client must present an ID card proving Chinese
citizenship or a legal document that states qualifications to
represent a Chinese corporation before opening an account."
</P>
<P>
B-share markets for overseas investors have separate
regulations, the draft says.
</P>
<P>
Qiao says that China needs to have companies examined by the
government before they go public at the present stage, but some
legislators have complained that too much government intervention
leads to corruption and unfair practices.
</P>
<P>
To solve this problem, the draft sets down specific procedures
for government approval and the government has to provide an
explanation if a corporation is not allowed to list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Securities Law Being Proposed This Year (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Other changes or additions include:
</P>
<P>
-- Public companies can not issue new stocks if they are found
to have diverted income from stocks to uses other than those
authorized by the board of investors;
</P>
<P>
-- To curb speculation, stock brokers are not allowed to sell
stocks that have been purchased earlier the same day;
</P>
<P>
-- The National Audit Office is responsible for supervising
the accounts of securities exchanges, brokerages, accounts
settling agencies, and government securities management agencies;
</P>
<P>
-- General managers of securities exchanges are to be
appointed by the State Council securities management agencies.
</P>
<P>
To warn investors of the risks of speculation, the draft
clearly points out that investors are solely responsible for gains
and losses in the market. However, government bonds are not
covered by the law, Qiao says.
</P>
<P>
This law, with revisions based on a review by legislators this
session, should be generally feasible and should play a positive
role in the development of China's securities market, he says.
</P>
<P>
Since the first stock was issued in Shanghai in 1990, China has
opened two securities exchanges, listing 827 publicly-held
companies, by 237 stockbrokers and many agencies. The value of the
Chinese stock market is 2 trillion yuan, or 23.4 percent of the
GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
