<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 300 Military Weapons Surrendered in West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Home Affairs Minister
Katele Kalumba has disclosed that the country's move to capture
illegal firearms has started paying dividends with about 350
weapons being surrendered in its Western Province alone.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here Tuesday, Kalumba said the
illegal weapons were surrendered after two patrols of national
wildlife officers were sent to two areas in the province, Times
of Zambia reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to curb the country's ever rampant crime wave, the
Zambian government last month offered a month-old amnesty for
people with illegal firearms to surrender them to the police.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has been experiencing in the past months more and more
aggravated robberies, murders and other serious crimes committed
by criminals that are usually armed with deadly weapons.
</P>
<P>
The criminals have easy access to weapons since there are
about 68,000 private or illegal guns in the country with a
comparatively small population of 9.5 million.
</P>
<P>
Kalumba also warned that the government would take drastic
measures against those who failed to heed the amnesty on
firearms.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that organized crimes such as drug
trafficking, motor vehicle thefts and robberies were rampant in
the country.
</P>
<P>
On drug trafficking, the home minister said 4,314 suspects
were arrested between 1996 and June, 1998. Among them, 194 were
foreigners. Illegal drugs worth more than five million U.S.
Dollars were confiscated during the period.
</P>
<P>
Kalumba pledged his ministry's commitment to contain crimes by
using law enforcement agencies to the fullest.  
</P>
</TEXT>
