<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislature Setting Up Budget Watchdog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) - The Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislative body,
plans to set up a special sub-committee, the Budgetary Work
Committee, to oversee the nation's budget.
</P>
<P>
A bill to this effect proposed by the chairman and
vice-chairmen of the Standing Committee was submitted to the full
session of the standing committee today.
</P>
<P>
The committee will strengthen the legislative function by
validating the national budget with better allocation of the
budget, based on the reality and reflecting the interests of the
people, according to He Chunlin, secretary-general of the
NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Understanding the budget requires a special expertise, he
points out, and without a special sub-committee, the budgets of
the past were ratified by the legislature in a procedural way,
without studying the substance, even though it is related to the
country's social and economic affairs and macro-economic
controls. And, effective control of the budget is related to
social and economic development, state security, and the standard
of living, he says.
</P>
<P>
The proposal suggests the sub-committee be charged with the
following duties:
</P>
<P>
-- Assisting the NPC and its Standing Committee in examining
the nation's budget, budget adjustment plans, and implementation;
</P>
<P>
-- Working out and studying drafts of laws related to finance,
the budget, and taxes and related laws and regulations, with
authorization from the NPC Standing Committee chairman and
vice-chairmen;
</P>
<P>
-- Carrying out other tasks of the NPC Standing Committee
chairman and vice-chairmen and assisting the NPC Finance and
Economic Committee.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also suggests Guo Zhenqian, the vice-chairman of
the NPC Finance and Economic Committee and former auditor-general
of the National Audit Office, head the sub-committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cataract Patients Benefit From Inexpensive Lens Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Millions of cataract patients
across China will be able to have their eyesight restored by
paying much less for new artificial lenses which started rolling
off the production on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The producers of these intraocular lenses (IOL), a key material
which must be implanted during cataract surgery, will turn out
100,000 lenses next year, and will double the annual output by the
year 2000, according to the IOL plant in the city of Suzhou in
east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Increased production will help keep the price for each IOL
under 10 U.S.dollars from their current cost of 300-1,000 yuan
(36-125 dollars), making them much more affordable for most
Chinese patients, according to Zhou Yongyao, director of the
Suzhou General Factory of Medical Instruments.
</P>
<P>
He also promised to keep the price unchanged in the next decade
while the factory supplies IOLs to ophthalmological institutions
and national medical teams which travel nationwide to perform
operations on patients in poor and remote areas.
</P>
<P>
Among the nine million blind people in China, four million
cannot see because of cataract. Public health experts fear that
cases of cataract blindness may increase among an increasingly
elderly and growing population.
</P>
<P>
The IOL plant, involving s total investment of five million
yuan, is an important part of Sight First China Action, a
rehabilitation project jointly launched last year by Lions Clubs
International, the Chinese Disabled Persons Federation (CDPF) and
the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to perform 1.75 million cataract operations
for patients across China over a five year period, as well as to
provide better facilities and training for local ophthalmologists,
said Kajit Habanananda, president of Lions Clubs International.
</P>
<P>
"With the opening of the new IOL plant, we are able to help
even more people regain their eyesight and see the world again,"
the president said at the opening ceremony Tuesday in Suzhou.
</P>
<P>
Experts with the CDPF estimate that the rate of IOL implants
among cataract patients will rise to over 40 percent, from the 20
percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Sight First China Action is the largest cooperative charity
campaign between the Chinese government and Lions Clubs
International, the world's largest service club organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
