<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Trades Weaker Pre-Christmas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar drifted
off further Wednesday, suffering the effects of weak commodity
prices and thin pre-Christmas trade.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 61.39 U.S. cents from 61.47
late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Commodity prices remained at low levels with the commodity
research bureau index closing at 189.11 points.
</P>
<P>
The local currency slipped lower Tuesday night in offshore
trade on the bearish outlook for commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange dealers said the soft volumes exaggerated the
downward move in the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the close the Australian dollar was trading at 71.41
Japanese yen from 71.95 and 1.0239 German marks from 1.0297.
</P>
<P>
The local currency is expected to continue to trade in the
tight range Thursday, ahead of the Christmas break.
</P>
<P>
The week between Christmas and the New Year is not expected
much busier in terms of volume, though some market participants
have speculated the Australian dollar may fall off to the
60.00-U.S.-cent level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
