<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania: Foreign Troops in Congo for Own </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 23 (Xinhua) - Tanzania has blamed the
escalation of war in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) on
the military involvement by some African countries to "safeguard
their own interests", according to an official communique
released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister for Foreign Affairs and International
Co-operation Jakaya Kikwete, quoted by the communique, said
Tuesday that the crisis in DRC could easily turn into a war in
the Great Lakes region because of foreign intervention.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in the DRC is being worsened by the involvement
of foreign countries in the conflict which are safeguarding their
interests," Kikwete said.
</P>
<P>
However, Kikwete, who just returned from a meeting of
Organization of African Unity (OAU) held in Ougadougou, Burkina
Faso, said that some encouraging efforts have been made as key
players in the crisis began to meet.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe and Rwandan Vice President
Paul Kagame met last week," he said. "It is encouraging to see
the two leaders who are on opposite sides of the conflict
meeting."
</P>
<P>
Claiming to be neutral in the DRC conflict, Tanzania recalled
its military advisors immediately after the conflict broke out on
August 2 while other neighboring countries rushed their troops to
either side of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The war has so far already drawn in Angola, Namibia, Zimbabwe,
Sudan, and Chad on the DRC President Laurent Kabila's side while
the Tutsi-led rebels are reportedly backed by Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete said that the Fourth Ordinary Session of the Central
Organ of the OAU Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management
and Resolution held on December 17 has persuaded the concerned
countries to pull out of the DRC in order to find a lasting
peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism about signing of a cease-fire agreement
between warring parties at a two-day regional summit expected to
convene in Lusaka at the end of this month and the subsequent
deployment of a UN peacekeeping force in the DRC to monitor to
the peace process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
