<HEADLINE> UAE Committed to Environment Protection: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates'
decision to join a United Nations agreement to combat
desertification reflected its policy to protect the environment,
a senior official has said.
</P>
<P>
Salem Masri Al Dhaheri, director of the Federal Environmental
Agency told the Gulf News daily Tuesday that the UAE has
officially joined the agreement on October 21, after the Foreign
Ministry submitted its ratification document to the U.N..
</P>
<P>
"According to the agreement, the UAE's membership will start
on January 19, 1999," said Al Dhaheri.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the signatories should be committed
to fighting desertification and drawing up effective and long-term
strategies towards that end.
</P>
<P>
Till August 1997, 107 countries have joined the agreement, out
of which 16 are Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Qatar is the only Gulf Cooperation Council country that has
yet to sign the agreement, which was endorsed in Paris in
1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
