<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Farmers Expect Bumper Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean farmers
expected bumper harvest in the season between November this year
to April next year thanks to the widespread rains with a sunny
spell now needed to prevent water-logging of some maize and to
stop nutrient leaching.
</P>
<P>
The latest crop and livestock report issued in Harare Tuesday
said that about 80 percent of the country had so far received
above normal rainfall since the onset of the rains, the daily
Herald report wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Weeding was the major activity in most areas, while planting
and land preparation continued in almost all provinces, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
It said despite water-logging and leaching in some areas, the
maize crop in communal lands was at the early vegetative stage
and was in fair to good condition.
</P>
<P>
The cotton crop and the tobacco crop are generally in good
state countrywide, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
