<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, December 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia's top legislator said Tuesday that the State
Duma has closed debates on ratifying the START II treaty in the
aftermath of the military strikes on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The militaristic action against Iraq, conducted in the
immediate proximity to the southern borders of the Commonwealth
of Independent States, should seriously prompt the strengthening
of the defense capability of not only Russia but the CIS as a
whole," said Gennady Seleznyov, speaker of the State Duma, or
lower house of parliament. "We must start developing our common
defense doctrine so that in the future no one could have
illusions about the possibility of knocking us off one by one,"
Seleznyov's spokesman Mikhail Belyat quoted him as saying. He
also urged the United Nations to immediately start an inquiry
into the activity of Richard Butler as head of the U.N. Special
Commission on Iraq (UNSCOM), and dismiss him from office.
(Russia-US-START II)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen on Tuesday
started a trip to the Gulf where he will meet with American
troops just off the mission of air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon did not provide Choen's schedule for the brief
visit beginning early on Wednesday for the sake of tight security
in the region. But defense officials said he would meet Air
Force, Navy and other troops to express Washington's thanks for
the four days of bombing at 100 Iraqi military targets. The
United States currently has more than 20,000 troops in the Gulf
region, including nearly 10,000 aboard the aircraft carriers
Enterprise and Carl Vinson steaming in the Gulf. (US-Gulf-Cohen)
</P>
<P>
- - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The European Central Bank (ECB) decided Tuesday to
set the unitary key interest rate for the 11 nations joining
monetary union next month at 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at the ECB's last council meeting
before the launch of the euro. ECB President Wim Duisenberg
announced it on the same day evening in Frankfurt. He said,
interest rates in the euro zone were already "very low by
historical standards", and ruled out a possibility of swift
lowering of lending rate. The ECB wanted to maintain this rate
for the "foreseeable future," he added. With starting of the Euro
as of next January, the ECB will be in charge of setting the
interest rates for the whole euro zone. (Germany-Bank-Interest
Rates) 
</P>
