<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Octuplets' Parents Thank Worldwide Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The parents of the
world's first octuplets born alive expressed their thanks Tuesday
for the support they received from the world over.
</P>
<P>
"We are very appreciative of the worldwide support over the
past few days, particularly the prayers and spiritual connection
at this time of the year," Nkem Chukwu and Iyke Louise Udobi said
in a statement released by Texas Children's Hospital in Houston,
where their babies are under intensive care.
</P>
<P>
The couple, who are Nigerian Americans, also thanked the
physicians, nurses and staff of the hospital, saying that all of
the family's concern at this time are the mother and the babies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the hospital in its seventh online press briefing
on Tuesday afternoon said that there has been an outpouring of
concern and warm wishes for this family from all over the world.
"Companies, organizations and individuals have already begun
calling in donations for Ms. Chukwu and the octuplets," it said.
</P>
<P>
Hospital sources said the mother is in good condition and has
shown marked improvement since surgery early Monday morning to
control bleeding. Her physicians said that if she continues to
improve at this rate, she would be discharged later in the week.
</P>
<P>
The octuplets remain in critical condition in the neonatal
intensive care unit at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
At this time, the baby girl born on December 8 is being fed
formula through a nasogastric tube. The other seven babies, born
on December 20, are receiving total parenteral nutrition, a combi
nation of proteins, fats, electrolytes, glucose, vitamins and
minerals.
</P>
<P>
Five of the octuplets were examined Tuesday by cardiologists
and received echocardigrams to rule out a problem common in
premature births called patent ductus arteriosis. The fifth baby
was diagnosed with this problem and will be treated with
medication.
</P>
<P>
All eight are responsive to sound and light but remain
undisturbed and quiet on warming beds, the hospital said.
</P>
<P>
"The good news is that there hasn't been any dramatic change in
 the babies' conditions," the hospital said. "We don't look for
significant changes -- we're happy with small progressions."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
