<HEADLINE> Jordan Hopes Early Israeli Elections Won`t Affect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Jordan hopes the decision by the
Israeli Knesset (parliament) to hold early elections won`t affect
the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the peace process will continue, and that the
move in Israel to hold early elections will not cause a delay in
peace making," Foreign Minister Abdul Ilah Khatib was quoted as
saying Wednesday by the Jordan Times.
</P>
<P>
He said the kingdom will deal with the Israeli government
regardless of who is in power, but hoped that the peace process
"will not be held hostage" by internal political developments in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Knesset Monday approved at first reading, by 81 to
30 votes, a bill calling for early elections.
</P>
<P>
Two more readings are needed over the next few weeks for the
bill to become law, bringing elections both for the parliament and
the post of prime minister within three to six months instead of
in November 2000. 
