<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heart Disease, Cancer, Australians' Biggest Killers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Heart disease and cancer
remained the biggest killers of Australians last year, official
figures showed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said 28 percent of
deaths were caused by heart disease and 27 percent by cancer.
</P>
<P>
External causes, including car accidents, falls, drowning and
suicide accounted for six percent of all deaths.
</P>
<P>
People aged 65 or over accounted for 78 percent of all deaths,
the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
The figures also showed that for men aged from 20 to 69 years,
those who had never married died at rates two to four times higher
than for those who had tied the knot.
</P>
<P>
Single women also died at a higher rate than their married
counterparts, but by much smaller margins.
</P>
<P>
Overall, married people experienced lower rates of death than
those who were divorced, widowed or never married.
</P>
<P>
The ABS said Australians are among the most long-lived people
in the world, with life expectancies approaching those of people
born in Japan, Sweden, Hong Kong and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
A boy born in Australia could expect to live for 75.6 years,
while a baby girl could expect to live for 81.3 years.
</P>
<P>
Over the last 25 years, life expectancy at birth has increased
by about eight years for males and seven years for females.
</P>
<P>
Although Australia's population is both increasing and aging,
resulting in a rise in the absolute number of deaths, the death
rates for people of almost all ages are falling.
</P>
<P>
Births still outnumber deaths by about two-to-one. In 1997
there were 129,400 deaths and 252,100 births. 
</P>
</TEXT>
