<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Successful In Stopping Forex Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China has cracked down on
fraud and foreign exchange crimes to enforce the law and insure
its balance of payments and the stability of the renminbi.
</P>
<P>
There was a slower increase in China's foreign exchange
reserves this year in spite of a favorable foreign trade balance
and increased investment from abroad.
</P>
<P>
China had a balance of 26.7 billion U.S. dollars and 24 billion
U.S. dollars worth of direct foreign investment in the
January-July period, but foreign exchange reserves increased by
only 700 million U.S. dollars during the period.
</P>
<P>
An investigation has shown that various illegal activities were
the main cause of the slow increase. So, in June, the State
Council, China's highest governing body, instructed banks
and the State Administration of Foreign Exchange (SAFE) for a
national check on the use of foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
For the past six months, SAFE has examined customs declarations
worth more than 200,000 U.S. dollars and more each and has found
1.2 billion U.S. dollars worth of fraudulent behavior committed by
627 enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Public Security departments have 230 cases for investigation
and prosecution, involving 3.6 billion U.S. dollars and 3.9
billion HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
On October 7, SAFE decided to give lenient treatment to
enterprises committed fraud of more than 5 million U.S. dollars
if they would confess to their crimes, and by the end of October,
over 1,000 enterprises had confessed wrongdoings.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that these cases reveal the problems involved in
trying to enforce financial discipline and the lack of
controls. The state plans to tighten controls and to put an
on-line nationwide customs declaration inspection system into
operation next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
