<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
went into early holiday mode Wednesday with very thin volumes
resulting in a slightly softer market.
</P>
<P>
On the last full day's trade before Christmas, the benchmark
all ordinaries index drifted down 4.8 points to 2,755.0, coming
off an intra-day high of 2,768.6.
</P>
<P>
"The market's down contrary to a firm close on Wall Street,"
Morgan Stockbroking's Simon Reed said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the holiday spirit, weaker commodities prices also
had a stifling effect on the domestic market, Reed said.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 259.96 million stocks changing hands for
657.54 million Australian dollars (407.67 million U.S. dollars),
with falling stocks outnumbering rising stocks 494 to 446 and 400
stocks remaining steady.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index dropped 8.7 points to 953.8 while the
all industrials index shed 1.7 points to 4,955.7.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector lost 26.9 points to 6,300.
</P>
<P>
NAB dipped 3.29 cents, ANZ slid 10.2, while both CBA and
Westpac were gainers, adding 2.9 and three cents respectively.
</P>
<P>
Media giant News Corp was one of the gainers in the softer
market, adding five cents.
</P>
<P>
Among the telcos, AAPT was steady at 3.88 Australian dollars,
Telstra gained eight and Cable &AMP; Wireless Optus fell three cents.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, Rio Tinto fell 12 cents, WMC lost two
cents and BHP shed 17.1 cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index eased 23.1 points to 1,071.0.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney was 287.75 U.S.
dollars an ounce, compared to a close of 288.70 Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
