<HEADLINE> Extremist Group in Philippines Plans Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 23 (Xinhua) --The Abu Sayyaf Group, an
extremist group based in the Southern Philippines, plans to stage
retaliatory attacks following the killing of its leader last week,
a rebel group said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ustadz Shariff Julabbi, spokesman of the rebel Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF), said in Mindanao that at any given time
attacks may happen anywhere in provinces of Zamboanga del Norte
and Zamboanga del Sur, should security forces give the extremist
group the chance to do it.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sayyaf leader Abdurajak Abubakar Janjalani was killed in an
encounter with the police in Southern Mindanao on December 18.
</P>
<P>
Janjalani, the most wanted criminal in the country, was
responsible for a series of kidnapping, extortion and bombing
incidents in Mindanao. His group killed over 50 civilians in the
town of Ipil, Mindanao, in April l996.
</P>
<P>
The MILF spokesman said that the followers of Janjalani are
greatly affected by his death especially when he was slain while
the Muslim community was observing Ramadan, an Islamic religious
activity, during which strict fasting was being observed from dawn
until sunset.
</P>
<P>
"The MILF expressed condolences to the family of Janjalani not
as a bandit leader but as a Muslim brother," he said.
</P>
<P>
Southern Command Chief Angelo Reyes said Tuesday the Abu Sayyaf
group has more or less 400 members, 30 of whom were direct
followers of the slain leader and are based in the southern
province of Basilan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
