<HEADLINE> Stranded Somali Refugees Returning Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- More than half of some 800
Somali refugees stranded in Kenya's Indian Ocean port city of
Mombasa left by sea at mid-night Tuesday for the Kismayu port in
southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
They were provided with three ships by Moslem businessmen in
Mombasa after the nearby Jomvu Refugee Camp where they have been
staying for more than seven years was demolished by Kenyan
authorities last week.
</P>
<P>
Jomvu camp, which originally hosted more than 100,000 Somali
refugees, has finally closed, four years after Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi ordered all refugees to leave Coast Province, the
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said in a statement
available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Two UNHCR-organized convoys left Jomvu for Kakuma Refugee Camp
in northern Rift Valley Province last week, relocating some 750
refugees there.
</P>
<P>
The rest, about 158 families comprising some 800 people who
opted to return home, were dumped at Fort Jesus Museum in Mombasa
Sunday. They would receive three months of food aid from the
World Food Program, said the UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
Kenya shelters 188,000 refugees in the northeastern Dadaab and
northwestern Kakuma refugee camps, down from a maximum of 420,000
persons in 1992 following large scale repatriation to Somalia and
Ethiopia and the resettlement of more than 35,000 refugees to
third countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
