<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mental Anguish Compensation Claims Growing In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Liao Keli, an eight-year-old
boy in the Chinese city of Chongqing, southwest China, recently
got 340,000 yuan (40,000 U.S. dollars) in compensation for an
injury he received, the largest payment of its kind in China.
</P>
<P>
Liao sued the Chongqing Trolleybus Company and Chongqing
Electric Industry Company because of an electric shock he got from
trolleybus wires 3 years ago. He had to undergo 13 operations,
with great pain, for a two and a half year period.
</P>
<P>
In another case, a woman in Beijing got 260,000 yuan for mental
anguish caused by malpractice, when a physician left a piece of
gauze in her abdominal area after performing an appendectomy.
</P>
<P>
Qian Yuan, a 19-year-old college student who received 250,000
yuan in compensation for mental anguish, says, "We should learn to
use the law to protect our rights when we are wronged." She filed
the suit after security guards at a supermarket belonging to
Shanghai Watson Consumer Products Corporation forced her to strip
for an examination when they suspected her of being a pickpocket.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy to see that changes have taken place in this and
that the compensation payments better reflect the degree of mental
anguish," says Lu Lei, a lawyer. Lu explains that, although the
damage is not tangible, it causes great suffering to the victims,
and compensation in the past was generally very little and did not
teach others a lesson.
</P>
<P>
China used to pay little attention to compensating these
victims because of traditional ideas that human dignity could not
have a money value placed on it.
</P>
<P>
But, greater contact with other countries since the reforms and
opening up began, has made the Chinese understand the importance
of reparations, and the number of mental anguish cases has been on
the rise in recent years. There were only 13,565 such cases from
1988 to 1992, or 1.73 percent of the total number of cases.
</P>
<P>
China plans to have more specific laws in this field in the
future to ensure ample mental protection, says Zou Tingqing, the
vice-president of the Chongqing Supreme People's Court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
