<HEADLINE> hke122324 - Malaysia Investigates Japan's Self-Copy Paper Dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has started
preliminary investigations into the dumping of self-copy paper
from Japan which caused material injury to the Malaysian industry
producing self-copy paper, the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government's action was based on sufficient evidence that
this product dumping had indeed occurred in the country, thus
causing material injury to the Malaysian industry producing
self-copy paper, the ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
It said if the determination is affirmative, the government may
impose an anti-dumping duty at a level that would eliminate the
dumping which causes material injury.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, allegations were made by a domestic
self-copy paper producer -- Gamuda Paper Industries Bhd that the
imports of self-copy paper from Japan are being made in the
country and the alleged product is being sold in Malaysia at a
price that is much lower than the level at which it is being sold
in Japan, thus having a negative impact on the Malaysian domestic
industry.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has imposed anti-dumping duties on the same product
against Indonesia and the European Union (EU) since April 20,
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
