<HEADLINE> China Enjoys Yet Another Bumper Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China's 1998 grain harvest is
expected to reach last year's level of 490 million tons, according
to Minister of Agriculture Chen Yaobang.
</P>
<P>
Chen pointed to a drop in the cotton output was lower than last
year, but noted that the total output of more than 4.2 million tons
will meet demand on the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Output levels for oil, sugar, vegetables and fruit surpassed
1997 levels, with meat output rising four percent and milk by six
percent.
</P>
<P>
Total output for aquatic products grew five percent to 38
million tons.
</P>
<P>
Township enterprises achieved a total value-added of 2,400
billion yuan, up 17 percent on the 1997 figure. Related
enterprises created some three million new jobs for rural
residents during the year.
</P>
<P>
Chen also pointed to a one million hectare increase in land
dedicated to autumn crops.
</P>
<P>
He said the government adopted a series of measures to
reinforce the household contract system and reduce financial
burdens of farmers.
</P>
<P>
Favorable autumn weather conditions helped to secure the year's
bumper harvest, according to Chen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
