<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Export Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh earned 1.655 billion
U.S. dollars from export during the first four months of the
current fiscal year between July 1998 and June 1999, about 14
percent short of the targeted 1.933 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a 5-percent negative growth compared with
the earnings made during the corresponding period of the previous
fiscal year, The Daily Star Business reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the earnings would make it difficult to reach the
country's export target of 5.8 billion dollars for the current
fiscal year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
During the July-October period, the export of raw jute and jute
products were 60.83 percent and 11.88 percent respectively short
of the original targets, the report quoted Export Promotion Bureau
officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The exports of leather, handicraft, knitwear and chemical
products were all less than the targets. And the export of
garments, the country's major foreign exchange earner, also
registered a 9.69-percent fall.
</P>
<P>
Only tea and frozen foods recorded increases in export
earnings, of 12.9 percent and 14.86 percent respectively over the
targets.
</P>
<P>
The fall in export earnings has caused deep concern in the
government, and the National Export Committee would discuss the
situation on Thursday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The devastating flood that hit the country and the higher
currency devaluation in some Asian countries that export similar
items are two factors causing the sharp fall in Bangladesh's
export, a report in The Financial Express daily said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
