<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Fire Katyusha Rockets at North Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 23 (Xinhua) -- After eight Lebanese civilians
were killed in Israeli air raids, scores of Katyusha rockets were
fired Wednesday morning into Israel's northern areas, the Orient
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media and officials said at least 10 Israelis were
injured in the attack.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has
claimed responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
The Katyusha rockets are always used by Hezbollah as a means to
revenge Israeli killing of Lebanese civilians.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday afternoon, eight Lebanese civilians, including a woman
and her six children, were killed in Israel's air raids on Jinta
area near the country's eastern city of Belbek.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli strikes have raised to 28 the number of Lebanese
civilians killed in south Lebanon since the start of this year,
setting off outrage across the country.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese permanent representative to the United Nations Samir
Mubarak was instructed by Prime Minister Salim Hoss to submit to
the U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan a note of protest
containing the pictures of the killed woman and her children.
</P>
<P>
He asked Annan to distribute copies of the protest note among
the U.N. Security Council member states and the general assembly.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a self-styled security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
cross-border attack by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Spearheaded by Hezbollah, Lebanon's resistance movement has
since been fighting to oust the Israeli occupation forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
