<HEADLINE> Cambodia Disposes of Suspected Toxic Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 23 (Xinhua) -- About 500 soldiers, wearing
masks and anti-chemical clothes, Wednesday began to put 3,000 tons
of suspected Taiwanese industrial toxic wastes, dumped about 15 km
near Sihanoukville, into more than 10,000 gas barrels before
shipping them back to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The barrels will be welded shut before being stored in larger
containers until the wastes can be shipped back to Taiwan. The
cleanup could take up to at least ten days.
</P>
<P>
The suspected toxic wastes, shipped from Taiwan on November 30
by a local company Muth Vuthy, caused violent protests at the
weekend and panic among the residents. About ten thousand
residents were trying to flee to the capital Phnom Penh, fearing
being affected by the wastes.
</P>
<P>
Protests were fueled by reports that some people were dead and
others had fallen ill because of the wastes. Sihanoukville
Hospital reported one port worker dead and two others ill, but
medical workers could not confirm whether the cases were related
to the wastes.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that at least four died and 18 injured in the
protest and road accidents as residents flee the town.
</P>
<P>
Eight experts on chemical and hazardous waste from the Thai
Army arrived at Sihanoukville Tuesday to inspect the dump site and
plan to take a sample back to Bangkok for testing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
