<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SingTel Launches Large-Scale Skill Redevelopment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Telecom (SingTel)
will invest millions of dollars within half a year to retrain its
1,700 technical staff aged 35 or more in a bid to make their
employees keep pace with the development in technology.
</P>
<P>
SingTel CEO and President Lee Hsien Yang made the statement at
a ceremony Wednesday morning to launch the Skills Redevelopment
Program (SRP) for the SingTel Group.
</P>
<P>
Under the program jointly developed by SingTel, the Nanyang
Polytechnic, the National Trades Union Congress (NTUC) and the
Union of Telecom Employees of Singapore, 1,700 employees in the
technical grade, who are 35 or more in age and account for 14
percent of the total of the company's 12,000 employees, have been
identified to be eligible to undergo a new course in
telecommunications at the Nanyang Polytechnic starting in January
1999 with an aim to upgrade their skills to a level suitable to
the needs of the fast paced telecommunications industry and the
next millennium.
</P>
<P>
Those who complete the six-month Certificate Course in
Telecommunication and meet the criteria can continue to pursue a
three-and a-half-year part-time Diploma course also developed by
SingTel and Nanyang Plytechnic.
</P>
<P>
SingTel's SRP is part of a 220-million Singapore-dollar
nation-wide SRP effort under the administration of NTUC in a drive
to upgrade skill and enhance employability of the country's
workforce, and SingTel has emerged as one of the first companies
in Singapore to work with an academic institution to provide new
training opportunities for employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
