<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysia's Political Stability Tested in 1998 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Political tranquillity
enjoyed by Malaysians for many years was challenged in the year of
1998 in the wake of the sacking of deputy prime minister and
finance minister Anwar Ibrahim, an event sparking off an
undeniably difficult time for Malaysians.
</P>
<P>
The sacking of Anwar on September 2 amidst allegations of
sexual misconduct and his expulsion a day later from Malaysia's
largest ruling party -- the United Malays National Organization
(UMNO), of which he was the deputy president, for "low morals" --
were described as "the most shocking developments in Malaysia's
politics in recent years."
</P>
<P>
Anwar was brought into the government by Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad in 1982, appointed Deputy Prime Minister on
December 1, 1993, and declared on several occasions as Mahathir's
successor.
</P>
<P>
The political rupture between Mahathir, who is UMNO president,
and Anwar was however reportedly partly due to their odds over
monetary policies in dealing with the prevailing regional
financial crisis which dragged Malaysia's economy into recession
with gross domestic product declining 2.8 percent, 6.8 percent and
8.6 percent respectively in the first three quarters of the year.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir favored stimulating business with lower interest rates
while Anwar adhered to International Monetary Fund (IMF) style
policies particularly in maintaining tight monetary policies
including high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government is currently implementing expansionary
fiscal and monetary policies instead of the tight fiscal and
monetary polices pursued last year and early this year to
stimulate domestic consumer and economic activities.
</P>
<P>
After his dismissal, Anwar traveled around the country to
address public gatherings, calling for Mahathir's resignation and
reforms. He was arrested by police at his house on September 20
after addressing an illegal gathering of his supporters earlier in
the day at the National Mosque here, who later turned violent.
Anwar was detained the next day under the Internal Security Act.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was later charged with five counts of corrupt practices
and five counts of unnatural sex acts, but he denied all the
charges. His trial on four corruption charges out of the 10
charges began on November 2 in the High Court here and is still
continuing.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic events related to Anwar put at stake the political
tranquillity, which Malaysia, a multi-racial society, enjoyed for
a long time.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrations and even riots which followed shook the normally
tranquil capital city and dismayed many Malaysians as street
politics carried out by Anwar's supporters threatened public peace
and security.
</P>
<P>
Almost at every weekend in October and November, organized
illegal assemblies were held in several places in the federal
capital, which sometimes led to rioting. On a number of occasions,
police had to resort to stern actions to restore order by using
tear gas and water cannons to disperse the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
Facing the disturbing situation, Mahathir stressed the
importance of maintaining stability in the country and urged the
people to uphold the country's democratic system to ensure
continued peace and prosperity, saying "riots, demonstrations and
other unbecoming behaviors are not the ways Malaysians do things."
</P>
<P>
As the year of 1998 is drawing to a close, the fanaticism of
Anwar's supporters died out as no more demonstrations were seen in
the past three weeks at weekends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysia's Political Stability Tested in 1998 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Following the expulsion of Anwar from UMNO, keeping the party
united was a challenge facing Mahathir. To consolidate the party,
the party's Supreme Council purged the party by expelling 10 party
members and issuing notices to 18 others asking them to explain
why they should not be expelled. Most of them were known as
Anwar's strong supporters.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Zahid Hamidi, a strong supporter of Anwar, was forced to
resign as UMNO Youth Chief on October 2.
</P>
<P>
On December 13, UMNO amended its constitution at a special
general assembly in an effort to check money politics and tighten
discipline.
</P>
<P>
The amendments abolished the awarding of bonus votes for
candidates for the posts of party president and deputy president
introduced in the 1993 party election and replaced it with a
provision for eligibility based on a percentage system, under
which a candidate vying for the president's post must receive at
least 30 percent nomination from the 165 divisions, for deputy
presidency 20 percent, vice-presidency 10 percent and supreme
council membership five percent.
</P>
<P>
The amendments were observed to have been made to consolidate
the party's structure in the run-up to the party's election
scheduled for June next year.
</P>
<P>
Though many suggest that Mahathir appoint a deputy prime
minister at an early date to fill up the vacancy left behind by
Anwar, Mahathir, afraid of causing disunity among the seniors
within the party, is still unable to make decision on who could be
the next deputy prime minister before the party election as the
post is related to the UMNO deputy president's post.
</P>
<P>
Despite the political crisis in UMNO, the backbone of the
ruling Barisan Nasional (BN) (National Front) coalition
government, all BN component parties repeatedly expressed their
strong support for Mahathir's leadership as BN chairman.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, by taking advantage of Anwar's event,
opposition parties including Democratic Action Party (DAP), the
largest opposition party in the country, and the Islam Party of
Malaysia came into coalition along with some non-governmental
groups to form two organizations -- the People's Democracy Front
and the People's Justice Movement, but both were declared by the
authorities as illegal.
</P>
<P>
The move was, however, observed to indicate the opposition's
challenge to the ruling BN coalition in the coming general
election. The opposition publicly stated its objective of eroding
away the BN's two-thirds majority in the next general election
which is due to be held in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
An early general election was much talked about in the year.
All BN component parties have been directed by BN
Secretary-General Mohamed Rahmat to activate their respective
election machinery to guarantee no erosion to the coalition's
massive majority in the next general election. Speculation is rife
about the snap polls to be held by May next year.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Mahathir once said "Anyway, holding a general
election is a very big job. You need full attention and managing
the economy also need full attention. It is not necessary to
stretch our limited energy between managing the economy and the
elections."
</P>
<P>
It would be difficult to handle both the election and the
economy at the same time, he said, adding the BN government has to
focus on reviving the economy.
</P>
<P>
Observers said what is challenging Mahathir most is the
economic recovery his government needs to strive for. If the
government can manage an early recovery, it will surely win the
mandate of the people in the next general election, they said.
</P>
<P>
They also pointed out that developments on vacant UMNO deputy
president's post should be keenly observed as the developments may
affect the UMNO unity and stability, which are a prerequisite for
the political stability in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
