<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Sees Soaring Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Convictions for violent
crimes in New Zealand have increased by 65 percent in the past
decade, including shocking increases in the number of rapists,
kidnappers and robbers.
</P>
<P>
An NZ justice ministry report "Conviction and Sentencing of
Offenders in New Zealand: 1988 to 1997" shows:
</P>
<P>
-- Last year, 230 people were convicted of rape, an increase of
180 percent since 1988, though 1997's figure was the lowest in
the past five years;
</P>
<P>
-- Convictions for robberies jumped by 60 percent during the
past 10 years, and aggravated robbery convictions more than
doubled;
</P>
<P>
-- Last year, 1,113 people were found guilty of kidnappings or
abductions, up 113 percent from 1988;
</P>
<P>
-- Convictions for dealing in hard drugs have doubled since
1988; and
crimes against the justice system, including breaching bail and
obstructing or perverting the course of justice, have nearly
doubled in the decade.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, which was made public here Wednesday,
male offenders accounted for 84 percent of non-traffic offenses.
</P>
<P>
Offenders in their 20s were responsible for 45 percent of
crimes, of which 23 percent was committed by those in their 30s.
Teenagers accounted for 21 percent and those aged over 40
accounted for 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
A latest prison census showed that the number of people in
prison in the country has jumped by more than 70 percent and they
are serving longer sentences for more violent crimes than they
did a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
According to the census, which was taken on November 20, 1997,
there were 4,935 sentenced prisoners in New Zealand, a country
with a population of less than 3.8 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Out of Economic Recession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand economy has
 shrugged off the recessionary blues with higher-than-expected
growth in the third quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics New Zealand said Wednesday that the country's
economic activity in the third quarter rose by 0.7 percent after
one percent and 0.8 percent shrinks for the first and second
quarters respectively.
</P>
<P>
Local economists had expected a flat result for the quarter
before the official figure came out.
</P>
<P>
But Wednesday's result completed the worst year for the New
Zealand economy since 1992. The economy grew only 0.4 percent in
the year to September, the lowest result since September 1992.
</P>
<P>
Anyhow, the news about the positive growth in the third quarter
means "New Zealand is officially out of recession," the Evening
Post said.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Deputy Government Statistician Ian Ewing said in a
media release that the boost from growth was export-led with
industries such as forestry and manufacturing recovering after
falls in production earlier in the year. Exports were up 3.6
percent in the third quarter, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Wellington-based newspaper, the news gave a
boost to the New Zealand dollar, which has somewhat risen in its
valuation against the U.S. dollar. Short-term interest rates have
also risen with 90-day bank bills up from 4.5 percent to 4.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports showed business confidence in New Zealand has
been increasing in recent months and some sectors have shown
signs of growth. The forestry sector, which suffered at the peak
of the Asian economic crisis, has seen demand returning, with log
shipments to Japan and the Republic of Korea increasing. The
agricultural sector has also been boosted by a mild winter and
favorable growing conditions in spring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
