<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Announces "World's First" Oceans Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Australia Wednesday launched
a comprehensive, national plan to ensure the conservation of its
rich marine biodiversity and security for marine-based industries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Canberra, Australian Federal
Environment Minister Robert Hill claimed Australia is the first
country in the world to develop such a plan, entitled Australia's
Oceans Policy.
</P>
<P>
Nan Bray, chief of the Marine Research Center under the
Commonwealth of Scientific, Industrial Research Organization, said
Australia's marine and coastal resources currently contribute more
than 42 billion U.S. dollars a year to the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The minister added the plan will be "the guiding force in the
future use and care of Australia's marine and coastal resources,"
saying the federal government would allocate 30 million U.S.
dollars over three years for a range of actions associated with
its implementation.
</P>
<P>
"At the core of the policy is a commitment to ecosystem-based
management of our marine jurisdiction which will be implemented
through a new regional marine planning process."
</P>
<P>
Based on large marine ecosystems, regional marine plans would
integrate sectoral commercial interests and conservation
requirements, he said.
</P>
<P>
"To drive the implementation of the policy and the regional
planning process, the (federal) government will establish a
National Oceans Ministerial Board which will include all relevant
Commonwealth ministers."
</P>
<P>
The policy also sets out a range of initial actions to be
undertaken by the government, including additional funding to
improve understanding of the marine environment, increased support
for the declaration and management of new marine reserves in
Australian waters, measures to increase the effectiveness of
surveillance and enforcement of illegal fishing in Australia's
marine jurisdiction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Announces First National Water Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
announced the country's first national water policy which was
designed to ensure proper management and best utilization of water
resources, press reports here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the policy include comprehensive development
of main rivers, management of water resources in an efficient
manner, decentralization of management of water resources, and
ensuring availability of water to all elements of society.
</P>
<P>
The policy, which was approved by the cabinet on Monday after
comprehensive discussions by the National Water Council, was
announced by Water Resources Minister Abdur Razzak on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The policy set the guidelines for future water management in
both the public and the private sectors, Razzak said.
</P>
<P>
The framing of the policy was possible because of the signing
of the Ganges Water Sharing Treaty with India in 1996, he said.
The minister hoped that talks on sharing the waters of 53 other
rivers with neighboring countries would resume soon.
</P>
<P>
Under the policy, which would be reviewed periodically and
revised if necessary, the government through its agencies would
undertake comprehensive development and management of the main
rivers through a system of barrages and other structural and
non-structural measures, develop water resources of the major
rivers for multipurpose use, such irrigation, fisheries,
navigation and forestry.
</P>
<P>
The government would de-silt water courses to maintain
navigation channels and proper drainage, delineate water-stress
areas based on land characteristics and water availability for
managing dry season demand, and take steps to protect water
quality and ensure efficiency of its use.
</P>
<P>
The government would develop early-warning and flood-proofing
systems to manage flood, drought, and other natural disasters,
designate flood risk zones and take appropriate measures to
provide desired levels of protection for life, property, vital
infrastructure, agriculture and wetlands.
</P>
<P>
Regions of economic importance such as metropolitan areas,
airports and export processing zones would be fully protected
against floods as a matter of first priority, according to the
policy.
</P>
<P>
About the rural areas, the policy pointed out that the people
would be motivated to develop different flood proofing measures
such as rising of platform for homesteads, market places and
educational institutions, and adjusting the cropping pattern to
suite the flood regime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
