<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, December 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- The European Central Bank (ECB) decided Tuesday to set
the unitary key interest rate for the 11 nations joining monetary
union next month at 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at the European Central Bank's last
council meeting before the launch of the euro. ECB President Wim
Duisenberg announced it on the same day evening in Frankfurt.
(Germany-Bank-Interest Rates)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) Tuesday
announced the approval of 130 million U.S. dollars in financing
for private sector toll road linking Sao Paulo with Sorocaba and
Aracoiaba da Serra.
</P>
<P>
The financing is provided to Concessionaria de Rodovias do
Oeste de Sao Paulo to support the construction, upgrade,
operation, and maintenance of approximately 156 kilometers of toll
road between the three cities. (IDB-Financing-Brazil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The International Finance Corporation (IFC)
Tuesday announced the signing of agreements with the Bank of
America to establish a 100 million U.S. dollar fund that will
support trade finance to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The IFC, an affiliate of the World Bank Group which supports
private sector projects in developing countries, will guarantee 40
percent of the 100 million dollar exposure taken by the Bank of
America. (IFC-SKorea-Fund)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- A contract was signed early this week for oil
extraction in the Black Sea continental shelf by Romania's
National Agency for Mineral Resources and National Oil Petrom
Company and ELF AQUITAINE of France.
</P>
<P>
Romania's National Agency for Mineral Resources and National
Oil Petrom struck a deal in April over the exploring of
approximately 10,000 square kilometers off-shore the Black Sea. In
sea water less deep than 100 meters, Petrom will process 70
percent of the allotted shelf, while ELF 30 percent. ELF will
process 70 percent and Petrom 30 percent in waters from 100 to
1,600 deep. (Romania-France-Oil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WARSAW -- Poland registered a trade deficit of 16.3 billion
U.S. dollars in the first 10 months this year, up 3.2 billion
dollars from the same period last year, the Central Statistics
Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
During the period, imports increased 11.5 percent while exports
rose 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Central Statistics Bureau attributed the widened trade
deficit to the slump of Poland's exports to the European Union
(EU). (Poland-Foreign Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuelan imports will reach over 16.1 billion
dollars this year, 26 percent increase over last year, the
statistics and computer central office said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the January-October period, imports reached 13.1 billion
dollars, rising by nearly 26 percent over the 10.4 billion dollars
registered in 1997. (Venezuela-Imports-Soar)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Foreign investors have pumped one billion
U.S. dollars into tourism, commercial and industrial projects in
Panama over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Trade Ministry adviser Ricardo Duran said five percent
of his country's gross domestic product was produced by foreign
capital, which had helped create 50,000 jobs opportunities within
the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The privatization of the nation's telecommunication, water and
electricity agencies and the sale of its racetracks and casinos
had boosted the inflow of foreign funds. (Panama-Foreign
Investment) 
