<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mutant Gene For Heart-Rhythm Abnormality Identified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Researchers from Baylor
College of Medicine in Houston have located a gene responsible for
a heart-rhythm abnormality that can cause sudden death for
people under 35, the Circulation reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dr Robert Roberts and his colleagues found the gene's
approximate location by studying seven generations of a large
Canadian family with 10 people having this disorder. They studied
DNA from 149 members of the family and narrowed down the location
of the bad gene to an area of chromosome 3.
</P>
<P>
The disorder kills the muscle cells of the right ventricle of
the heart, which are replaced with fatty, fibrous tissue.
</P>
<P>
People with the disorder can be treated with implanted
defibrillators, drugs and surgery. A defibrillator shocks the
heart to restore a normal rhythm.
</P>
<P>
Dr Roberts said the immediate benefit of the discovery was the
ability to screen people who had the bad gene, and then implant a
defibrillator.
</P>
<P>
Dr Hugh Calkins, director of electrophysiology at Johns Hopkins
University, called the findings "a very significant
breakthrough". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
