<HEADLINE> Soeharto's Son-in-Law Says He Will Not Relinquish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Prabowo Subianto, a son-in-law
of former president Soeharto, has said that he would not
relinquish his Indonesian citizenship, according to national
newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the newspapers on Tuesday, Prabowo, former chief
of the Army's Special Force (Kopassus), acknowledged that he had
been granted Jordanian citizenship by a Royal Decree.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Amman, the capital of Jordan, the
office of Prime Minister Fayez Tarawneh has confirmed that
Prabowo's bid for citizenship had been endorsed by a royal decree
on December 10.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo said in his letter that he has rejected the granting of

honorary Jordanian citizenship because Indonesia does not
recognize dual
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo and two other Kopassus senior officers were sanctioned
in August after a military council found they were involved in the
abduction and torture of political activists earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo was given an early retirement, while the two others
were barred from holding operational positions within the Armed
Forces (ABRI).
</P>
<P>
ABRI Commander Gen. Wiranto, announcing the sanctions on the
three Kopassus officers in August, did not rule out the
possibility of the three being brought before a military court
should more evidence surface during the trial of 11 Kopassus
members.
</P>
<P>
The military trial of the 11 soldiers, including seven
noncommissioned officers, on charges of kidnapping and torture is
due to begin here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Tuesday, Justice Minister Muladi warned Prabowo
against accepting Jordanian citizenship.
</P>
<P>
"We do not recognize dual citizenship... Once someone accepts
another citizenship, he loses his Indonesian citizenship," Muladi
said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that change in the nationality of Prabowo will not
affect the legal prosecution against him for alleged kidnapping of
pro-democracy activists.
</P>
<P>
However, it would be difficult to try Prabowo at the military
tribunal if he is in Jordan because Indonesia has no extradition
agreement with the Middle Eastern country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
