<HEADLINE> Thai Official Gets UK Backing for WTO Top Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Prime Minister
Supachai Panitchpakdi has got Britain's backing for his bid to
become the World Trade Organization's (WTO's) new chief.
</P>
<P>
Britain has sent a letter expressing support for Supachai, also
Commerce Minister, to become WTO's next director general,
according to Thai foreign ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
Britain was the first European Union country to officially
announce support for Supachai.
</P>
<P>
"The EU is very largely in favor of the next director-general
of the WTO being from a developing country. In this context, the
UK had decided to support Dr Supachai. We are now working to
persuade our EU partners to rally around his candidature," British
ambassador to Thailand James Hodge said in the letter, available
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I am delighted to be able to give you this positive news.
Speaking personally, I very much hope that Dr Supachai's candidacy
will be successful," he said.
</P>
<P>
Other candidates include New Zealand's former prime minister
Michael Moor, Morocco's ex-trade minister Hassan Abouyoub and
Canada's former trade minister and current high commissioner in
London Roy MacLaren.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland and Brazil will conduct consultations with other
WTO members to sound out their opinions on January 11, while the
General Council of WTO will make a final decision on January 18.
</P>
<P>
The decision will be based on the density of support,
geographical distribution of expressed backing and level of
acceptance. The result is expected to be announced by the end of
next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
