<HEADLINE> Kyrgyz Probe Continues on Corruption in Finance Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyz Interior Minister
Omurbek Kutuyev said Tuesday that the probe into alleged
corruption and embezzlement in the Finance Ministry is continuing.
</P>
<P>
Kutuyev told lawmakers that charges of embezzlement, fraud and
corruption had been brought against detained ministry officials.
About 35 such facts have been checked, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyz Prosecutor-General Asanbek Sharshenaliyev said that if
the corruption charges are not confirmed, the cases will be
closed.
</P>
<P>
He said a task force combating corruption plans to detain and
bring charges against several more state officials. He did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Talaibek Koichumanov has sharply condemned
the arrest of Finance Ministry officials, saying the announcement
of an indictment prior to a court decision is a gross violation
of human rights.
</P>
<P>
He also accused law-enforcement officers of blackmailing and
slandering the defendants.
</P>
<P>
"A good initiative to combat corruption, advanced by the
president, has been discredited," Koichumanov said.
</P>
<P>
"The Finance Ministry is not guilty of anything," the minister
claimed.
</P>
<P>
The former Soviet republic has stepped up its fight against
corruption in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Hot lines are being installed in the country to handle complai
nts about corrupt officials, Shirshenaliyev, the
prosecutor-general said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Shirshenaliyev heads the Coordinating Council Against
Corruption and Economic Crime, a task force created by President
Askar Akayev on December 19.
</P>
<P>
The council, which includes representatives of security and
law enforcement structures, tax agencies, customs structures and
the prosecutor's office, will take steps to tighten the struggle
against corruption, Shirshenaliyev said.
</P>
<P>
Government comptrollers and the Presidential Administration
will be assisting the council, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new structure will control the investigation of all
corruption charges in the country, the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
He said 383 officials had been dismissed over the past five
years on charges of corruption. The majority of crimes involving
abuse of office were committed by low-level rather than by senior
officials, Shirshenaliyev said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Announces "World's First" Oceans Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Australia Wednesday launched
a comprehensive, national plan to ensure the conservation of its
rich marine biodiversity and security for marine-based industries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Canberra, Australian Federal
Environment Minister Robert Hill claimed Australia is the first
country in the world to develop such a plan, entitled Australia's
Oceans Policy.
</P>
<P>
Nan Bray, chief of the Marine Research Center under the
Commonwealth of Scientific, Industrial Research Organization, said
Australia's marine and coastal resources currently contribute more
than 42 billion U.S. dollars a year to the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The minister added the plan will be "the guiding force in the
future use and care of Australia's marine and coastal resources,"
saying the federal government would allocate 300 million U.S.
dollars over three years for a range of actions associated with
its implementation.
</P>
<P>
"At the core of the policy is a commitment to ecosystem-based
management of our marine jurisdiction which will be implemented
through a new regional marine planning process."
</P>
<P>
Based on large marine ecosystems, regional marine plans would
integrate sectoral commercial interests and conservation
requirements, he said.
</P>
<P>
"To drive the implementation of the policy and the regional
planning process, the (federal) government will establish a
National Oceans Ministerial Board which will include all relevant
Commonwealth ministers."
</P>
<P>
The policy also sets out a range of initial actions to be
undertaken by the government, including additional funding to
improve understanding of the marine environment, increased support
for the declaration and management of new marine reserves in
Australian waters, measures to increase the effectiveness of
surveillance and enforcement of illegal fishing in Australia's
marine jurisdiction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
