<HEADLINE> More Swifts On Southern Chinese Island Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China's island province of
Hainan now has 40 rare swifts that were on the verge of extinction
in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say that the return of the birds is the result of
the 70-sq.km. Dazhoudao Marine Nature Reserve, which was opened in
September, 1990 and to an improved environmental and greater
awareness of local people.
</P>
<P>
The swift population declined drastically over the past century
because of the excessive hunting of the bird for its edible nests,
which are popular among the southern Chinese. 
</P>
</TEXT>
