<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Imports Soar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan imports will reach
over 16.1 billion dollars this year, 26 percent increase over
last year, the statistics and computer central office said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the January-October period, imports reached 13.1 billion
dollars, rising by nearly 26 percent over the 10.4 billion dollars
registered in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The increase was due to uncertainty preceding the recent
presidential elections, prompting store-owners to hoard supplies
they believed could be sold at a higher price in case of a crisis
after the voting.
</P>
<P>
The office said that exports would total 1.5 billion dollars in
November and 1.3 billions in December.
</P>
<P>
The United States is Venezuela's largest supplier, with 7.1
billion dollars worth of sales, or 44 percent of the total,
followed by Colombia with 915 million dollars, Japan with 858
million dollars and Mexico with 732 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Electrical supplies dominated the imports with a 30.3 share
of the market.
</P>
<P>
They are followed by transportation materials with 18.6
percent, and chemicals with 10.2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
