<HEADLINE> Italy Signs New Social Pact to Create Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 22 (Xinhua) -- A new social pact designated to
create jobs and boost economic growth was signed here Tuesday by
Italian central government, industrial associations, labor unions
and local governments.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact, companies will reduce their welfare
contributions to employees by 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
This would lead to a 1.2 percent drop in labor costs by 2003.
</P>
<P>
The pact also rules that the government will allocate 1.6
trillion lire (about 1 billion U.S. dollars) in 3 years for the
job-training program for young people.
</P>
<P>
A permanent body will be set up inside the prime minister's
office to monitor the implementation of the pact.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, Italian Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema described the pact as "dynamic", and called on the whole
society, not only the government, to take its own responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the labor union and industrialist sector hailed the
pact as good and necessary and stressed that they would monitor
its implementation. 
