<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Minister: Oil Prices to Remain Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The prospect of oil prices
staying low are crushing Venezuela's hopes of an increase in crude
revenues for the next three years, Deputy Energy and Mines
Minister Dolores Dobarro said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dobarro said that world oil inventories were still large and
Iraq was selling more crude at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
She said that prices would recover only if other producers
committed themselves to cut output.
</P>
<P>
Dobarro said Venezuela would completely comply with its
commitment to reduce output by 525,000 barrels a day by January 1,
when production would go down by 80,000 to 100,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
She said the latest pledge by Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and
Mexico to postpone further cuts until December 1999 could be
shared by other countries in an extraordinary meeting of the
Organization of Petroleum Producing Countries (OPEC) and by
non-OPEC producers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
