<HEADLINE> New Trainer Wants to Help Tyson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Tommy Brooks is hoping to
be Mike Tyson's trainer when the former heavyweight champion
prepares his comeback fight next month.
</P>
<P>
"In order for him to be successful again, to regain the title,
we have to go back to the old style," Brooks said of Tyson, who
will fight South Africa's Francois Botha on January 16 in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking to get that head movement, nonstop punching
and stepping aside and around his opponent back," Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
Brooks joined Tyson's camp as head trainer seven weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
"When you are a new trainer, what I've been concentrating on
is not trying to change his style but working to get back to the
Mike Tyson of old," Brooks said. "I was worried that I might not
have enough time, but he showed me he was taking everything in
that we were working on. He was putting his punches together in
bunches and not trying to take him out in one punch. He was not
squaring up."
</P>
<P>
Brooks has helped Holyfield to beat Tyson twice. "The thing
that happened to Mike was he wasn't in shape and he was getting
hit by punches that he didn't think he could get hit by and he
just lost it," Brooks said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
