<HEADLINE> Referee Could Sue Di Canio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Referee Paul Alcock is
considering possible legal action against Sheffield Wednesday
forward Paolo Di Canio for pushing him over during the game with
Arsenal three months ago.
</P>
<P>
The 44-year-old official claims he is still suffering physical
problems as a result of the incident and has not refereed a
Premiership match since November 7.
</P>
<P>
"I have been having physiotherapy since the incident but it
has gone much deeper than that," he told the Daily Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"Last Tuesday, I was in a London hospital under general
anaesthetic, having treatment on my back, to put a disc back in
place.
</P>
<P>
"Since the incident I have had continuous pins and needles
down my left leg. I was unable to sleep without painkillers and
it has been hard for me and my family," he said.
</P>
<P>
Di Canio was suspended for 11 matches following the incident
and is currently in dispute with Wednesday for failing to return
to the club following compassionate leave.
</P>
<P>
He is still in Italy and says he is suffering from stress and
depression but the club has now imposed a third fine on him,
taking his total bill, including legal costs, to around 125,000
pounds.
</P>
<P>
"If he does require medical attention, then he should be seen
by our own medical advisors. We have not been able to get that
message across to his lawyers. But it's very difficult to
communicate when it's on a one-way basis," said Wednesday
secretary Graham Mackrell.
</P>
<P>
Referee Alcock insists he has no personal grudge against Di
Canio but is concerned about his loss of earnings.
</P>
<P>
"If I refereed him in a match tomorrow, it would be fine for
me as long as he kept within the rules. But I can't make any
further comment on the specific incident because it could
seriously jeopardise the course of action I wish to take," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"It would be dangerous for me to say any more. All I will say
is that I am determined to get fit and get back to refereeing. It
has been so frustrating sitting on the sidelines," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
