<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- US West, a major sponsor
of Salt Lake's 2002 Winter Olympics, has written a letter to the
organizing committee to protest the "unsavory allegations" during
the games bidding.
</P>
<P>
According to a local press report, US West has asked Salt Lake
Organizing Committee President Frank Joklik to "clarify what has
transpired and what actions the Olympic movement taking to
address these issues."
</P>
<P>
"The ideals and spirit of the Olympic Games and the values and
high standards of the athletes draw companies like ours to
sponsor the process and to use these powerful symbols of
commitment, determination and fair play in our marketing,
management and community affairs efforts," Mark Roellig, US
West's general counsel, said in a December 18 letter.
</P>
<P>
"The very core of these ideals and the spirit of the games are
now under scrutiny and perhaps tainted. This is an extremely
serious issue for all of us," Roellig wrote.
</P>
<P>
Other sponsors also showed their concern to this scandal.
</P>
<P>
"We've expressed our concerns to the International Olympic
Committee and they assured us they will take swift and decisive
action, and we will monitor them to ensure that," said Ben
Deutch, spokeman for Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
"As an Olympic sponsor, we are very concerned that the
Olympics keep the proper perspective and any allegation raises a
concern," said Bill Berry, spokeman for Delta Air Lines, another
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
SLOC is worrying that sponors will not offer their aid for the
Games, which still need more than $600 million of the estimated
$1.4 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell, the former Senate Democratic leader is chairman of
the USOC's Ethics Oversight Committee. The committee will carry
out its investigation this week. 
</P>
