</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Although Saturday's U.S House of Representatives
vote to impeach President Bill Clinton was only the second time a
president has ever been impeached, the public didn't seem much
interested.
</P>
<P>
Only about one-third of American adults said they paid very
close attention to the impeachment proceedings, according to
findings released on Tuesday by the Pew Research Center for the
People &AMP; the Press.
</P>
<P>
"There was no suspense involved" in the impeachment, said
Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center. "They
(Americans) don't like it. They see it as an exercise in
partisanship."  (US-Impeachment-Poll)
</P>
<P>
