<HEADLINE> Hospital Updates Conditions of Octuplets, Mother </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The mother of world's
first octuplets to be born alive is "alert, happy and excited"
following surgery early Monday morning to control bleeding,
according to the latest press briefing released by Texas
Children's Hospital Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The hospital, where the octuplets are under intensive care, has
so far put out six press briefings online on the conditions of the
babies and their mother.
</P>
<P>
"The babies had an uneventful night," Tuesday's briefing said.
"All eight infants remain critical, but stable."
</P>
<P>
According to the hospital, Baby E (the fifth), the smallest of
the octuplets with the birthweight of 320 grams, measures
lengthwise at 25 centimeters. She is approximately the size of a
Beanie Baby toy and can fit in a woman's hand.
</P>
<P>
Baby A is now off the ventilator; babies B through H are all
breathing with the assistance of ventilators. Two of them are
receiving oxgen ranging from 35 percent to 100 percent. All are
being kept sleepy and quiet under a plastic blanket on a warming
bed and have been treated with surfactant replacement to help with
premature lung diseases. All eight infants are receiving
intravenous sugar and fluids, the hospital said.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's briefing identified the mother as Mrs. Chukwu.
"Companies, organizations and individuals have already begun
calling in donations for Mrs. Chukwu and the Chukwu octuplets,"
the hospital said.
</P>
<P>
A previous briefing quoted Dr. Leonard Weisman, chief of
neonatology service at the hospital, as saying that premature
babies such as the octuplets have an 85 percent chance of
surviving and leading productive lives. "They are all critically
ill, (but) several are showing improvements," the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
The first baby was born on December 8, and others on December
20. Their mother underwent surgery to control bleeding about 18
hours after delivering seven of the octuplets by Cesarean section.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
