<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania, France Sign Oil Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 22 (Xinhua) -- A contract was signed early
this week for oil extraction in the Black Sea continental shelf by
Romania's National Agency for Mineral Resources and National Oil
Petrom Company and ELF AQUITAINE of France.
</P>
<P>
Romania's National Agency for Mineral Resources and National
Oil Petrom struck a deal in April over the exploring of
approximately 10,000 square kilometers off-shore the Black Sea. In
sea water less deep than 100 meters, Petrom will process 70
percent of the allotted shelf, while ELF 30 percent. ELF will
process 70 percent and Petrom 30 percent in waters from 100 to
1,600 deep.
</P>
<P>
The total operation cost amounts to 1.5 billion U.S. dollars.
Under the contract, the two oil companies benefit from exclusivity
in this area for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
ELF AQUITAINE, a world leader in oil extraction operating in
deep water, will invest 10 million U.S. dollars in the first phase
and is expected to come up with 500 million dollars afterwards.
</P>
<P>
The contract becomes effective after it receives appropriation
of the Romanian government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Replaces France in Confederations Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- European champion Germany
will replace World Cup winner France in next year's
Confederations' Cup in Mexico, FIFA, soccer's governing body,
said in Zurich, Switzerland, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The tournament will take place July 24 to August 4 _ four days
earlier than planned _ to accommodate the Germans, FIFA said.
</P>
<P>
After weeks of debate over the schedule and to the anger of
FIFA and local organizers, France withdrew because of clashes
with its domestic and European obligations, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The French move reflected a feeling by many European squads
that the Confederations Cup is an unnecessary feature on an
overcrowded soccer calendar.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the world champion and host nation, FIFA
invited continental champions Brazil, New Zealand, Egypt and
Saudi Arabia along with South American and CONCACAF runners-up
Bolivia and the United States to participate in the competition.
</P>
<P>
Germany will play in Group B in Guadalajara against Brazil,
the United States and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
FIFA initially moved the eight-nation event from January 8-20
to July 28-August 8 to placate France. The French federation said
it accepted this, but then changed its mind because the French
national league begins its 1999-2000 championship on July 28.
</P>
<P>
France then asked for the competition to be moved to the start
of the summer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Lack of Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- European markets appeared lost
of energy Tuesday after the unexpectedly strong run Monday took
the wind from their sails.
</P>
<P>
London's blue chips suffered a modest downturn in a thin
uninspiring session, with little in the way of seasonal cheer for
any bulls still trading before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 ended 33.2 lower at 5843.3 on volume of 620m
shares traded. The leading index had put together a slim advance
in early trade, in spite of a dismal session in Asia.
</P>
<P>
But sentiment was gradually eroded as players looked to
consolidate on Monday's impressive 2.3 percent surge. The
performance on Wall Street depressed sentiment further, as trading
there was flat to lower, with the technology sector under sharp
pressure.
</P>
<P>
German shares closed firmer as dollar strength was countered by
Wall Street's losses. The Dax index ended trading off intra-day
highs at 4825 - up 44 points.
</P>
<P>
French stocks were little changed in late deals, coming off
firmer levels in line with Wall Street's drift.
</P>
<P>
The Cac 40 gained 17 points to close at 3820. Overall market
sentiment remains bullish, although there is little fresh news
providing direction for investors, said a trader in Paris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
