<HEADLINE> NATO to Continue Open-door Policy and Enlargement: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 22 (Xinhua) -- NATO would continue its
open-door policy as a priority even after the Washington Summit in
1999, and also its enlargement, Klaus Naumann, chairman of the
NATO Military Committee said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Romania's Prime Minister Radu Vasile,
Klaus Naumann, now on a visit to Romania, stressed the important
role played by Romania as NATO's partner that went beyond the
Partnership for Peace (PfP)and said interoperability between
Romanian Armed Forces and NATO forces was an essential criterion
in assessing Romania's admission request.
</P>
<P>
He said Romania, a candidate country having many assets and
having appreciatedly contributed to NATO operations in Bosnia,
still had to make efforts for a better state economy.
</P>
<P>
NATO would design a special program for the candidate countries
as part of the enlargement process, in order to bring them closer
to the Alliance, he added.
</P>
<P>
Romania's Prime Minister Radu Vasile said that Romania had been
undergoing a straight and painful process of economic and
institutional reforms, yet it had been paying special attention to
the restructuring and modernization of its armed forces as well to
better performances to attain interoperability with NATO forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
