<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC, Bank of America Agree to Enhance Trade in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) Tuesday announced the signing of agreements with
the Bank of America to establish a 100 million U.S. dollar fund
that will support trade finance to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The IFC, an affiliate of the World Bank Group which supports
private sector projects in developing countries, will guarantee 40
percent of the 100 million dollar exposure taken by the Bank of
America.
</P>
<P>
The facility is a one year facility that can be renewed to
accommodate a second year and will support South Korean trade
activity by broadening the availability of short-term trade
finance. It will give selected South Korean banks better access to
letters of credit confirmations, and bankers acceptances, support
trade between South Korea and other markets as well as increase
the number of South Korean banks with access to trade financing.
</P>
<P>
After its merger with the Nations Bank in September, this year,
the Bank of America is the largest U.S.-based commercial bank with
total assets of 595 billion dollars. It has offices in 37
countries and has business in over 190 countries and regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
