<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Central Bank Decides Interest Rate at 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Central Bank (ECB)
decided Tuesday to set the unitary key interest rate for the 11
nations joining monetary union next month at 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at the European Central Bank's last
council meeting before the launch of the euro. ECB President Wim
Duisenberg announced it on the same day evening in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
He said, interest rates in the euro zone were already "very low
by historical standards", and ruled out a possibility of swift
lowering of lending rate. The ECB wanted to maintain this rate for
the "foreseeable future," he added.
</P>
<P>
With starting of the Euro as of next January, the ECB will be
in charge of setting the interest rates for the whole euro zone.
</P>
<P>
The new rate will be applied as the "initial tender rate" at
which the ECB will lend money to commercial banks in the euro zone
and will determine overall lending rate levels in the 11 euro
countries.
</P>
<P>
As a transitory measure, the deposit rate will be initially set
at 2.75 percent and the marginal lending rate at 3.25 percent. As
of 21 January the rates for these lending facilities will be set
at 2 per cent and 4.5 per cent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The temporary narrowing of the corridor was aimed to ensure a
smooth launch of the new euro money market, the ECB said.
</P>
<P>
On New Year's Eve, the ECB will set the final conversion rates
of the euro with other currencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0293 </DOCNO>
