<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Public Don't Pay Close Attention to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Although Saturday's U.S
House of Representatives vote to impeach President Bill Clinton
was only the second time a president has ever been impeached, the
public didn't seem much interested.
</P>
<P>
Only about one-third of American adults said they paid very
close attention to the impeachment proceedings, according to
findings released on Tuesday by the Pew Research Center for the
People &AMP; the Press.
</P>
<P>
"There was no suspense involved" in the impeachment, said
Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center. "They
(Americans) don't like it. They see it as an exercise in
partisanship."
</P>
<P>
The poll was based on telephone interviews December 19-21 with
805 adults who participated in a similar poll December 9-13.
Clinton's job approval ratings jumped from 61 percent in the first
poll to 71 percent in the more recent one.
</P>
<P>
The poll also shows 67 percent said House members who voted for
impeachment did so for political reasons; 25 percent said
lawmakers voted for impeachment because they felt Clinton's
actions warranted removal from office.
</P>
<P>
The poll's margin of error was plus or minus 4 percentage
points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Prime Minister Backs Minister on House Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair on Tuesday defended Trade Secretary Peter Mandelson after
the minister admitted receiving a 373,000 pound (620,000 U.S.
dollars) secret loan from Paymaster General Geoffrey Robinson.
</P>
<P>
Blair's official spokesman said the matter was considered
closed after it had been looked into by the Cabinet Secretary Sir
Richard Wilson.
</P>
<P>
He said he was satisfied Mandelson had properly "insulated
himself" from an investigation into Robinson's business affairs.
</P>
<P>
Mandelson said earlier that he had been given a "stiff kicking"
by "mischievous" newspapers -- but had not needed to declare the
loan, which he put towards buying a home, as it was "a personal
arrangement".
</P>
<P>
Mandelson paid 475,000 pounds (780,000 U.S. dollars) for the
house in west London's fashionable Notting Hill district more than
two years ago while in opposition.
</P>
<P>
After the trade secretary was appointed to his current post in
Summer, he was informed the Department of Trade and Industry would
be investigating Robinson's financial dealings.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Mandelson would now be writing to the new
Registrar for Members Interests inviting her to rule on whether he
had breached Commons rules by not declaring the loan.
</P>
<P>
Mandelson said the outstanding amount was 332,000 pounds
(548,000 U.S. dollars). He paid interest at a base rate and hoped
to finish paying it all off soon.
</P>
<P>
Downing Street said ministerial code only required ministers to
ensure they were not placed in a situation where they might be
facing a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Conservative MPs have criticized the loan and
demanded more details and a full inquiry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
