<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Federal Reserve Leaves Interest Rates Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve
policy-makers decided to keep short-term interest rates unchanged
at this year's final meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Open Market Committee's decision, announced by Fed
spokeswoman Lynn Fox after the meeting ended at 12:55 p.m., was in
line with most economists forecasts. It leaves the federal funds
overnight bank lending rate at 4.75 percent, the level it has been
at since it was last cut by a quarter percentage point on Nov. 17.
The discount rate on emergency loans from the central bank remains
steady at 4.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Fed has cut official interest rates three times over the
past three months in a move to shield the U.S. economy and nervous
financial markets from the fallout of the world economic slump
that began in Asia last year.
</P>
<P>
With the U.S. economy demonstrating continued growth which
began in March 1991, many economists said the Federal Reserve is
likely to wait for fresh evidence of a slowdown in this country
before cutting rates again. It will probably get the evidence, but
not before its next meeting scheduled for Feb. 2-3, 1999. The next
year's second meeting has been set for March 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
