<DOCNO> XIE19981223.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Athlete to Lower New Year Ball in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese gymnast Sang Lan,
injured and paralyzed in the 1998 Good-Will Games here five months
ago but showing encourage to face physical difficulties, will
press the button in Times Square to signal the beginning of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old girl will be a special guest at the
celebrations expected to draw some half million New Yorkers.
Together with New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, she will press the
button to lower the New Year Ball at the Square, it was announced
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sang Lan, who fell to the ground from uneven parallel bars in
July, has been hospitalized in New York, receiving care and warmth
from the medical team and American society. She has never lost
heart in recovery and has continued to do exercises and learning
English.
</P>
<P>
Appearing with a smile at a press conference here Tuesday, she
waved hands to reporters and said Happy New York in English.
</P>
<P>
"I'm happy and I love you all," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We feel honored to share our New Year event with Ms. Sang Lan.
She has become an international symbol of encourage and
inspiration," said Brendan Sexton, president of Times Square
Business Improvement, which organizes the function.
</P>
<P>
The ball-lowering activity, begun 94 years ago, has been
featuring outstanding individuals.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, 88-year-old Oseola McCarty, a laundress who
donated her life savings of 150,000 U.S. dollars to the University
of Southern Mississippi, was invited to participate in the Time
Square festivities.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, five school children from each borough of New York
were selected to join the celebration of the 100th anniversary of
the combination of the boroughs into one city.
</P>
<P>
The 500-pound aluminum lightening ball will drop from a
flagpole 77 feet tall in the last 60 seconds of 1998 amid cheers
of the crowd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
